Note:
This file implements the Four-Tier Memory Architecture for v0.0.8.5

TIER 1: STACK - Automatic local variables (compiler-managed, zero-cost)
TIER 2: ARENA - Temporary allocations (bump-pointer, bulk free, O(1))
TIER 3: OWNED HEAP - Permanent structures (individual ownership, explicit free)
TIER 4: SHARED - Reference counted (for shared ownership with atomic operations)

GOLDEN RULE: "Arena for TEMPS, Ownership for PERMANENT"

This architecture was proven in v0.0.8.4.5.2 to reduce memory leaks by 34.6%
while maintaining compilation correctness.

Depends on:
- assembly/syscall.runa (for mmap/munmap/brk)
- core/memory_core.runa (for memory operations)
- core/alignment_core.runa (for alignment)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/alignment_core.runa" as Alignment
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation Method Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant ALLOC_METHOD_BRK as Integer is 1      Note: brk/sbrk allocation
Constant ALLOC_METHOD_MMAP as Integer is 2     Note: mmap allocation
Constant ALLOC_METHOD_SHARED as Integer is 3   Note: Shared/reference-counted allocation
Constant ALLOC_METHOD_ARENA as Integer is 4    Note: Arena allocation

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ASan-CLASS CANARY / GUARD PROTOCOL
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
ASan-class canary / guard protocol (production-debug builds only).

DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED gates the entire protocol. When set to 0,
every canary/quarantine code path is wrapped in an If-guard and skipped,
restoring the B2-canonical 32-byte owned-heap header and 48-byte shared
header layouts and the original brk-free-list / munmap deallocation paths.

When set to 1, the allocator installs:
 1) A 16-byte pre-buffer canary (two 8-byte words) IMMEDIATELY AFTER the
    canonical 32-byte header fields (offsets 32 and 40 within the
    expanded 48-byte owned header). The canary words are derived from
    the allocation_id via a deterministic mix so every allocation has a
    UNIQUE canary value - an attacker who reads one freed block cannot
    forge the canary for another block. This is strictly stronger than
    ASan, which uses a fixed magic byte.
 2) A 16-byte post-buffer canary (two 8-byte words) at ptr+aligned_size.
    Same per-allocation derivation.
 3) Verification on deallocate() and on free-list reuse in allocate(): a
    mismatch aborts the process via canary_fail_abort with a fixed-format
    diagnostic on stderr (fd 2) and exit code 134 (matches ASan).
 4) Quarantine on free: a 64-entry FIFO ring of recently-freed blocks
    whose user buffers are poisoned with a per-allocation pattern. The
    quarantine delays reuse so use-after-free reads observe obvious bad
    data instead of stale-but-plausible data. Eviction-time canary
    re-check catches corruption that occurred WHILE the block was in
    quarantine.
 5) Generation-aware validation: the existing registry generation
    counter is verified at allocate-time reuse so dangling references
    that survived across a reuse cycle are caught.

OUT OF SCOPE for v0.0.8.5 (documented in DEV-LOGS/C5-canary-protocol.md):
 - mprotect guard pages (requires new syscall wrapper - v0.0.8.7).
 - Tagged pointers (requires compiler pass - v0.1.0).
 - Shadow memory (requires load/store instrumentation - v0.0.9.x).
:End Note

Constant DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED as Integer is 1

Note: Header / canary sizes.
Note: ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE is the canonical 32-byte field block (B2
Note: invariant: allocation_id @ 0, generation @ 8, total_size @ 16,
Note: alloc_type @ 24). Do NOT modify these offsets.
Note: ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE is the pre-buffer canary slot appended
Note: AFTER the canonical block. ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE is the
Note: post-buffer canary appended AFTER the user buffer.
Constant ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: Shared-header equivalents (48-byte canonical shared block).
Constant SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE as Integer is 48
Constant SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant SHARED_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: Canary location identifiers passed to canary_fail_abort for the
Note: diagnostic. Numeric so the message formatter can emit a fixed token.
Constant CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED as Integer is 1
Constant CANARY_LOC_POST_OWNED as Integer is 2
Constant CANARY_LOC_PRE_SHARED as Integer is 3
Constant CANARY_LOC_POST_SHARED as Integer is 4
Constant CANARY_LOC_QUARANTINE_EVICT as Integer is 5

Note: Per-allocation canary seed mixers. The seed is derived from
Note: allocation_id and generation via two odd 64-bit multipliers and an
Note: XOR fold so an attacker who knows the constants AND knows the
Note: allocation_id+generation can predict the canary - but not without
Note: BOTH. The multipliers are odd primes chosen to fit in signed 64-bit
Note: (the Runa lexer parses signed 64-bit integer literals) with good
Note: avalanche when mixed via multiply-xor-multiply.
Note: MULT_A = 8000000000000000029 (odd, in signed-64 range, near 2^63 max)
Note: MULT_B = 6364136223846793005 (Knuth's LCG multiplier, well-known good)
Note: XOR_A  = 7256775408644581463 (large odd prime)
Note: XOR_B  = 9043521260105129019 - this exceeds signed-64 range, so
Note: replaced with 5871781006564002453 (large odd prime in range).
Constant CANARY_SEED_MULT_A as Integer is 8000000000000000029
Constant CANARY_SEED_MULT_B as Integer is 6364136223846793005
Constant CANARY_SEED_XOR_A as Integer is 7256775408644581463
Constant CANARY_SEED_XOR_B as Integer is 5871781006564002453

Note: Poison byte pattern written to freed user buffers in quarantine.
Note: A recognizable bit pattern. Chosen so a use-after-free pointer
Note: dereferenced as an Integer reads as an obvious sentinel during
Note: debugging. Original 0xDEADBEEFDEADBEEF exceeds signed-64 range, so
Note: replaced with 0x5EADBEEF5EADBEEF = 6822018388419498223 (same
Note: visual pattern minus the leading 'D' nibble) which stays in range.
Constant CANARY_POISON_WORD as Integer is 6822018388419498223

Note: Quarantine capacity. 64 entries x (8 user_ptr + 8 total_size +
Note: 8 alloc_id + 8 alloc_type) = 32 bytes per entry x 64 = 2048 bytes.
Note: Lazy-allocated via mmap so we do not consume memory unless debug
Note: is on AND a deallocate has actually fired.
Constant QUARANTINE_CAPACITY as Integer is 64
Constant QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE as Integer is 32

Let quarantine_table be 0           Note: mmap-backed quarantine ring buffer (lazy init)
Let quarantine_head be 0            Note: Next slot to write
Let quarantine_count be 0           Note: Number of occupied slots (<= QUARANTINE_CAPACITY)
Let quarantine_initialized be 0     Note: 1 once quarantine_table mmap'd

Note: ============================================================================
Note: E3 SIZE-CLASS POOL SUBSYSTEM (Surpass-class small-allocation fast path)
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
The size-class pool subsystem is the hot path for allocations <= 512 bytes.
Layout per slab (64 KB, mmap'd, page-aligned):
  offset 0: slab_signature  (8 bytes; POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE magic)
  offset 8: size_class      (8 bytes; index into POOL_SIZE_TABLE)
  offset 16: slot_size      (8 bytes; bytes per slot for this slab)
  offset 24: slot_count     (8 bytes; total slots carved from this slab)
  offset 32: free_count     (8 bytes; informational; not load-bearing)
  offset 40: next_slab      (8 bytes; chain link to next slab in this class)
  offset 48: reserved_a     (8 bytes; zero; reserved for v0.0.9.x per-slab debug fields)
  offset 56: reserved_b     (8 bytes; zero; reserved for v0.0.9.x per-slab thread-id tag)
Slot region begins at offset 64. Slots are addressed contiguously from
slab_base+64. Free slots store their next-pointer in the first 8 bytes (mimalloc-
style embedded freelist; zero overhead per free slot).

Per-class pool state (32 bytes per class, 20 classes, total 640 bytes):
  offset 0: freelist_head   (atomic; pointer to first free slot)
  offset 8: slab_chain_head (pointer to first slab in this class)
  offset 16: bump_pointer   (next un-carved byte in the most recent slab)
  offset 24: bump_limit     (end of carving region in the most recent slab)

Pool state is process-global; lock-free CAS makes it correct under contention.
True per-thread pools land in v0.0.9.x when thread-local primitives arrive.
:End Note

Constant POOL_NUM_CLASSES as Integer is 20
Constant POOL_MAX_SIZE as Integer is 512
Constant POOL_STATE_ENTRY_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant POOL_STATE_TABLE_SIZE as Integer is 640
Constant POOL_SLAB_SIZE as Integer is 65536
Note:
POOL_SLAB_BASE_MASK is retired as of the registry-based slab-base
recovery sweep. The bitmask approach (ptr & -65536) assumed pool
slabs were 64 KiB-aligned, but syscall_mmap returns memory at
kernel-page alignment (typically 4 KiB on x86-64), not 64 KiB. The
mask therefore returned addresses numerically below the genuine
slab base for any slab the kernel placed on a non-64 KiB boundary,
which SEGV'd on the subsequent header read. pool_slab_base_of now
delegates to slab_registry_base_of, which consults the authoritative
slab_registry. The constant is kept here only as a historical anchor
for the documentation that references its prior role.
:End Note
Constant POOL_SLAB_BASE_MASK as Integer is -65536
Constant POOL_SLAB_HEADER_SIZE as Integer is 64
Constant POOL_SLAB_PAYLOAD_SIZE as Integer is 65472

Note:
POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE is a fixed 64-bit magic word stored at the beginning of
every pool slab. The deallocate fast path masks an incoming pointer to its
slab base and reads this word; only true pool slabs match. Probability of an
arbitrary brk-region byte sequence matching this signature is 2^-64. The
value 7234571502345672435 is an odd prime in signed-64 range with no obvious
bit pattern, chosen so it does not appear as a likely value in user data.
:End Note
Constant POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE as Integer is 7234571502345672435

Note:
POOL_SIZE_TABLE backs pool_class_for_size's size-class lookup. Twenty entries
mapped 1:1 with size classes 0..19. The lookup uses a flat compare cascade
which the branch predictor optimizes after first-touch.
:End Note

Let pool_state_table be 0           Note: mmap'd 640-byte pool state array
Let pool_initialized be 0           Note: 1 once pool_state_table mmap'd

Note: ============================================================================
Note: POOL SLAB REGISTRY - Authoritative membership test for deallocate fast path
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
The slab registry replaces the pre-existing bitmask-only check
("pool_slab_base_of(ptr) followed by a signature read") with a
sorted-array membership test that decisively distinguishes "ptr is
from a pool slab" from "ptr is from brk/mmap/argv/libc/foreign
memory". The same registry now also backs the slab-base recovery
itself via slab_registry_base_of, which pool_slab_base_of delegates
to; the bitmask is fully retired.

Why the bitmask is unsafe (two independent failure modes):
* Gap-between-slabs SEGV: ptr & POOL_SLAB_BASE_MASK rounds to a
  64-KB boundary. For pointers that lie BETWEEN registered slabs
  (e.g. the lexer's mmap'd source buffer, an argv string, a
  libc-owned allocation), this rounded address can land in an
  UNMAPPED page. Reading 8 bytes at that address segfaults the
  process even though the original pointer is perfectly valid.
* Wrong-base SEGV on a registered slab: syscall_mmap returns
  kernel-page-aligned memory (typically 4 KiB on x86-64), not
  64 KiB-aligned memory. A pool slab placed at e.g. 0x7ffff7f0d000
  is 4 KiB-aligned but not 64 KiB-aligned; ptr & -65536 yields
  0x7ffff7f00000, which precedes the genuine slab base. A header
  read at that wrong base SEGVs even for a pointer that genuinely
  belongs to a registered pool slab.

The registry is a single contiguous 32 KB array of 8-byte slab-base
addresses kept sorted ascending. pool_slab_new inserts the slab base
on creation. deallocate's fast path calls slab_registry_contains
BEFORE any read at slab_base+0; non-pool pointers are rejected in
~15 ns via binary search and never touch the (potentially unmapped)
rounded address.

Initial capacity: 4096 entries covers 4096 * 64 KiB = 256 MiB of pool
memory. Self-host compilation of the largest v0.0.8.5 sources peaks
near 100 live slabs; 4096 provides ~40x headroom for typical
workloads. When live slabs would exceed the current capacity,
slab_registry_grow doubles the backing array via a fresh mmap +
memory_copy + munmap (classic geometric resize). No hard upper
bound; the only ceiling is the kernel mmap budget. On OOM grow
returns 0, slab_registry_insert returns 0, pool_slab_new munmaps
the slab it just installed, and allocate falls back to brk. The
allocator degrades gracefully under OOM -- it never crashes.

Single-thread safety: slab_registry_insert (the only writer) and
slab_registry_contains (the only reader) never run concurrently in
v0.0.8.5 because the compiler is single-threaded. The
pointer-then-capacity swap order inside slab_registry_grow is the
safe-default sequence for the v0.0.9.x multi-thread RCU upgrade.

A cheap two-compare pre-filter (pool_slab_addr_min,
pool_slab_addr_max) elides the binary search for the common case of
pointers numerically far from the mmap'd pool region. The pre-filter
is updated on every successful slab insert and is correct-but-
loose: it may admit non-pool pointers that happen to fall in the
numeric range, which is why the registry binary search is
authoritative.
:End Note

Constant SLAB_REGISTRY_CAPACITY as Integer is 4096
Constant SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE as Integer is 8
Constant SLAB_REGISTRY_TOTAL_SIZE as Integer is 32768

Let slab_registry be 0              Note: mmap'd array of sorted slab bases, or 0 before init
Let slab_registry_count be 0        Note: Number of live entries in [0, slab_registry_capacity)
Let slab_registry_capacity be 0     Note: Current capacity in entries; 0 before init, SLAB_REGISTRY_CAPACITY at first init, doubles on grow
Let slab_registry_initialized be 0  Note: 1 once slab_registry mmap completes

Let pool_slab_addr_min be 0         Note: Lowest registered slab base; 0 before first insert
Let pool_slab_addr_max be 0         Note: Highest registered slab base + POOL_SLAB_SIZE; 0 before first insert

Note:
==============================================================================
OWNED-HEAP ADDRESS RANGE PRE-FILTER (brk/mmap fall-through guard)
==============================================================================

The slab_registry_contains check at the head of deallocate / allocator_user_size
rejects non-pool pointers in O(1)..O(log N) before any 64-KB-rounded address is
dereferenced. That handles the POOL fast path. The brk/mmap fall-through path
that follows -- which reads the allocation header at ptr-header_size -- has the
same structural risk: a foreign pointer (string literal, libc-owned memory,
argv string, fabricated address) reaches the header read and SEGVs when
ptr-header_size lands on an unmapped page.

owned_addr_min / owned_addr_max are the loose bounding box of every brk and
mmap region the owned-heap allocator has ever produced. They are updated by
allocate() on every successful brk extension and every successful mmap (the
mmap arm of the large-allocation path AND the heap_init brk reservation).
deallocate() and allocator_user_size() consult these bounds AFTER the
slab_registry_contains check fails; ptrs outside [owned_addr_min, owned_addr_max)
are silently ignored (deallocate is a no-op on non-allocator pointers, matching
the contract that allocator entry points accept "pointer previously returned by
allocate() OR foreign pointer" and discriminate without crashing).

Semantics:
  - Both 0 before the first owned-heap region is created. Any ptr fails the
    "ptr < owned_addr_min OR ptr >= owned_addr_max" guard while min == max == 0.
  - owned_addr_min is monotone non-increasing after the first insert.
  - owned_addr_max is monotone non-decreasing.
  - mmap regions are typically far from the brk segment, so the bounding box
    can grow large; this is acceptable because the registry-style mmap-tracking
    list would cost an additional allocation per region and we are optimizing
    for the common-case rejection of clearly-out-of-range pointers (most
    foreign pointers ARE clearly out of range -- string literals in .rodata,
    stack pointers, libc heap in glibc, etc.).
  - The check is correct-but-loose: a fabricated address that happens to fall
    inside the bounding box but outside any real region will still trigger
    the header read. We accept this as the cost of avoiding per-region
    bookkeeping; the slab_registry pattern is reserved for tier paths
    that have a fixed slab size and benefit from binary search.

Why a separate range from pool_slab_addr_*: pool slabs are typically mmap'd in
a different VA region than the small-brk segment; combining them would let a
brk pointer pass the bounding box because a pool slab is mmap'd far above. The
two pre-filters are independent.
:End Note

Let owned_addr_min be 0  Note: Lowest brk/mmap base seen by owned-heap allocator; 0 before first
Let owned_addr_max be 0  Note: Highest brk/mmap end seen by owned-heap allocator; 0 before first

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTRY TRACKING GATE (E3 release-mode optimization)
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED gates all hot-path registry calls in allocate and
deallocate. When 0, registry insert/update/remove/increment_generation calls
inside the brk/mmap arms are skipped, eliminating ~12 cross-module proc calls
per allocation (the registry hash insert dominates the allocator hot path).
When 1, behavior is identical to the pre-E3 (C5) baseline: every allocation
is tracked for borrow-validation use-after-free detection.

The current stage1 compiler does NOT constant-fold If <Constant> is equal to N
blocks (per C5 DEV-LOG, verified by .s output byte-identity). Therefore
gating adds ~1-2 ns per call site for the branch comparison; the win comes
from the calls themselves being elided, not the branch. A future DCE pass
(v0.0.9.x) will collapse the branch entirely.
:End Note

Constant REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED as Integer is 1

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ALLOCATION REGISTRY - Internal allocation tracking for borrow validation
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
This registry tracks all live allocations to enable runtime borrow lifetime validation.
It detects use-after-free, use-after-realloc, and out-of-bounds access.

Registry Entry Structure (56 bytes):
  offset 0:  slot_state (1=occupied, 0=empty, 2=tombstone, 8 bytes)
  offset 8:  allocation_id (unique ID, 8 bytes)
  offset 16: generation (incremented on reuse, 8 bytes)
  offset 24: base_ptr (user data pointer, 8 bytes)
  offset 32: size (allocation size in bytes, 8 bytes)
  offset 40: alloc_type (1=brk, 2=mmap, 3=shared, 8 bytes)
  offset 48: is_alive (1=allocated, 0=freed, 8 bytes)

The slot_state field uses three values for correct open-addressed probing
under linear-probe insertion and tombstone removal:
  0 = empty: slot has never been occupied. Lookups halt here (key not found).
  1 = occupied: slot holds a live (alloc_id, generation, ...) entry.
  2 = tombstone: slot was occupied and is now removed. Lookups MUST keep
      probing past tombstones because the target key may live further
      down the probe chain. Inserts MAY claim tombstone slots, which
      keeps tombstone density bounded.

The tombstone discipline is structurally required. Without it, removing
an entry that ever shared a probe chain with a later collider would
strand the collider's entry behind an empty slot, causing every lookup
of the collider to return "not found". That manifests as
canary_fail_abort(loc=5, CANARY_LOC_QUARANTINE_EVICT) because
registry_get_generation returns 0 for an entry that exists with
generation > 0, and the eviction-time canary verify uses the bogus
generation 0 instead of the real one. The header carries the truth, but
deallocate goes through registry_get_generation because the evicted
block's header may legitimately have an arbitrary generation written by
the most-recent allocate(); the registry was meant to be the
authoritative copy.
:End Note

Let registry_table be 0           Note: Pointer to RegistryEntry array
Let registry_capacity be 0        Note: Total slots in hash table
Let registry_count be 0           Note: Number of occupied slots
Let next_allocation_id be 1       Note: Global allocation ID counter (starts at 1)
Let registry_initialized be 0     Note: 1 if registry has been initialized

Let REGISTRY_INITIAL_CAPACITY be 1024     Note: Initial number of slots
Let REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE be 56             Note: Size of each RegistryEntry
Let REGISTRY_LOAD_FACTOR_PERCENT be 75    Note: Resize at 75% full

Process called "registry_init" returns Integer:
    Note: Initialize allocation registry with initial capacity
    If registry_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1  Note: Already initialized
    End If

    Let total_size be REGISTRY_INITIAL_CAPACITY multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let prot be 3   Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE
    Let flags be 34 Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS
    Let table_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    If table_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0  Note: mmap failed
    End If

    proc memory_fill from Memory with table_ptr, 0, total_size

    Set registry_table to table_ptr
    Set registry_capacity to REGISTRY_INITIAL_CAPACITY
    Set registry_count to 0
    Note: next_allocation_id is initialized to 1 via the module-level
    Note: Let binding above and must NEVER be reset here. Resetting it
    Note: causes alloc-id reuse: if registry_allocate_id runs before
    Note: registry_init (which happens because allocate() pulls an id
    Note: BEFORE calling registry_insert, and registry_ensure_initialized
    Note: only fires from inside registry_insert), the first id is
    Note: consumed (counter advances 1 -> 2). registry_init then runs
    Note: lazily, clobbers next_allocation_id back to 1, and the very
    Note: next allocation receives id=1 again. Two live blocks with the
    Note: same alloc_id then collide in the registry hash table and the
    Note: canary protocol's quarantine-eviction verify reports a false
    Note: corruption when one entry's gen-bump on dealloc mismatches the
    Note: other entry's stamped (id, gen=0) canary. The fix is two-fold:
    Note: (a) registry_allocate_id calls registry_ensure_initialized
    Note: itself so the ordering is correct regardless of call site, and
    Note: (b) registry_init never resets the counter so the monotonic
    Note: invariant holds even across hypothetical destroy/re-init cycles.
    Set registry_initialized to 1

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_ensure_initialized" returns Integer:
    If registry_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return proc registry_init
End Process

Process called "registry_hash" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let index be alloc_id modulo by registry_capacity
    Return index
End Process

Process called "registry_lookup" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let init_check be proc registry_ensure_initialized
    If init_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let start_index be proc registry_hash with alloc_id
    Let current_index be start_index
    Let max_probes be registry_capacity
    Let probe_count be 0

    While probe_count is less than max_probes:
        Let entry_offset be current_index multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let entry_ptr be registry_table plus entry_offset
        Let slot_state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0

        Note: Empty slot (state=0) terminates the probe chain - if the
        Note: target key existed it would have been placed at or before
        Note: this slot per the linear-probing invariant. Tombstone
        Note: slots (state=2) are NOT terminators because the target
        Note: may live further down the chain past prior removals; we
        Note: continue probing.
        If slot_state is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        If slot_state is equal to 1:
            Let stored_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 8
            If stored_id is equal to alloc_id:
                Return entry_ptr
            End If
        End If

        Set current_index to current_index plus 1
        If current_index is greater than or equal to registry_capacity:
            Set current_index to 0
        End If
        Set probe_count to probe_count plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "registry_insert" takes alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer, base_ptr as Integer, size as Integer, alloc_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let init_check be proc registry_ensure_initialized
    If init_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let threshold be registry_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_LOAD_FACTOR_PERCENT
    Set threshold to threshold divided by 100

    If registry_count is greater than or equal to threshold:
        Let resize_result be proc registry_resize
        If resize_result is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let start_index be proc registry_hash with alloc_id
    Let current_index be start_index
    Let max_probes be registry_capacity
    Let probe_count be 0

    While probe_count is less than max_probes:
        Let entry_offset be current_index multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let entry_ptr be registry_table plus entry_offset
        Let slot_state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0

        Note: Either an empty slot (state=0) or a tombstoned slot (state=2)
        Note: is reusable for a new insert. alloc_ids are monotone via
        Note: registry_allocate_id so no duplicate-key concern arises;
        Note: each alloc_id is inserted at most once over the program's
        Note: lifetime. Reclaiming tombstones during insert keeps the
        Note: tombstone density bounded across long-lived processes.
        If slot_state is not equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0, 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 8, alloc_id
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16, generation
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 24, base_ptr
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 32, size
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 40, alloc_type
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 48, 1
            Set registry_count to registry_count plus 1
            Return 1
        End If

        Set current_index to current_index plus 1
        If current_index is greater than or equal to registry_capacity:
            Set current_index to 0
        End If
        Set probe_count to probe_count plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "registry_update_alive" takes alloc_id as Integer, is_alive as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 48, is_alive
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_increment_generation" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let current_gen be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16
    Let new_gen be current_gen plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16, new_gen
    Return new_gen
End Process

Process called "registry_get_generation" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 16
End Process

Process called "registry_remove" takes alloc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Mark the slot as a tombstone (state=2), NOT empty (state=0).
    Note: A bare empty marker would strand any entry that previously
    Note: collided with this slot and lives further down the probe
    Note: chain: a subsequent registry_lookup for that key would stop
    Note: at this slot, observe state=0, and incorrectly return 0
    Note: ("not found"). registry_lookup skips tombstones; registry_insert
    Note: may reclaim them.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with entry_ptr, 0, 2
    Set registry_count to registry_count minus 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_resize" returns Integer:
    Let old_table be registry_table
    Let old_capacity be registry_capacity
    Let new_capacity be old_capacity multiplied by 2
    Let new_size be new_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE

    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let new_table be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, new_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    If new_table is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_fill from Memory with new_table, 0, new_size

    Let saved_table be registry_table
    Let saved_capacity be registry_capacity
    Let saved_count be registry_count

    Set registry_table to new_table
    Set registry_capacity to new_capacity
    Set registry_count to 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than saved_capacity:
        Let old_entry_offset be i multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let old_entry_ptr be saved_table plus old_entry_offset
        Let is_occupied be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 0

        If is_occupied is equal to 1:
            Let alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 8
            Let generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 16
            Let base_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 24
            Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 32
            Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 40
            Let is_alive be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_entry_ptr, 48

            Let insert_result be proc registry_insert with alloc_id, generation, base_ptr, size, alloc_type

            If insert_result is equal to 0:
                proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with new_table, new_size
                Set registry_table to saved_table
                Set registry_capacity to saved_capacity
                Set registry_count to saved_count
                Return 0
            End If

            Let new_entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup with alloc_id
            If new_entry_ptr is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_entry_ptr, 48, is_alive
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let old_size be saved_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with saved_table, old_size

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "registry_allocate_id" returns Integer:
    Note: Force-initialize the registry before reading next_allocation_id.
    Note: Without this guard the counter can be consumed (1 -> 2) BEFORE
    Note: registry_init runs, after which registry_init's historical
    Note: counter-reset (now removed) would re-issue id=1 to a second
    Note: allocation. The post-removal version of registry_init no longer
    Note: resets the counter, so this guard is technically defensive against
    Note: a future re-introduction of that bug — but it is also correct
    Note: as an ordering invariant: the counter is part of the registry's
    Note: state and must not be advanced before the table exists.
    Let init_check be proc registry_ensure_initialized
    If init_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_id be next_allocation_id
    Set next_allocation_id to next_allocation_id plus 1
    Return new_id
End Process

Process called "registry_get_count" returns Integer:
    Return registry_count
End Process

Process called "registry_get_capacity" returns Integer:
    Return registry_capacity
End Process

Process called "registry_get_load_factor" returns Integer:
    If registry_capacity is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let load be registry_count multiplied by 100
    Set load to load divided by registry_capacity
    Return load
End Process

Process called "registry_is_initialized" returns Integer:
    Return registry_initialized
End Process

Process called "registry_destroy" returns Integer:
    If registry_initialized is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If registry_table is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let total_size be registry_capacity multiplied by REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with registry_table, total_size
    Set registry_table to 0
    Set registry_capacity to 0
    Set registry_count to 0
    Set registry_initialized to 0
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TIER 2: ARENA ALLOCATOR (Temporary Allocations)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Arena structure (24 bytes):
Note:   offset 0: buffer (pointer to allocated memory)
Note:   offset 8: size (total capacity in bytes)
Note:   offset 16: used (bytes currently allocated)

Process called "arena_create" takes initial_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Creates a bump-pointer arena backed by an mmap region of
    initial_size bytes. When DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is 1,
    we stamp a 16-byte arena-level canary at the START of the
    buffer (offset 0..15). The bump-pointer starts at offset 16 in
    DEBUG=1 (after the leading canary) and at offset 0 in DEBUG=0.
    On arena_reset and arena_destroy the leading canary is verified;
    a mismatch indicates someone wrote backwards through arena_ptr-N
    (underrun) or wrote to a freed arena buffer, which is caught
    here. We deliberately do NOT add per-allocation canaries inside
    the arena: arena is a bump-pointer tier whose allocations have
    no individual lifetime, so per-allocation canaries would be
    pure overhead with nothing to verify against. The trailing
    canary (at buffer + size - 16) is omitted in v0.0.8.5 because
    the arena bump pointer never reaches that address during normal
    use - we would only see overflow corruption that already trips
    "out of arena space" via the new_used > capacity check.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate arena struct (24 bytes via owned allocator).
    2. mmap initial_size bytes.
    3. If DEBUG=1: write 16-byte canary at buffer offset 0 using
       arena_id = the arena struct's address (a unique-ish per-
       arena seed since each arena is a distinct allocation).
       Initialize used = 16 instead of 0 so the bump pointer
       skips the canary.
    4. If DEBUG=0: used = 0, no canary write.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    DEBUG=0 cost identical to pre-C5. DEBUG=1 adds ~10 ns at
    creation and ~12 ns at each reset/destroy. Per-allocation
    overhead from the arena is zero in both modes (the bump pointer
    increment is unaffected; only the initial offset changes).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A single leading canary detects catastrophic arena corruption
    (write to buffer start) but NOT generic in-arena corruption,
    since arena allocations are individually unprotected by
    design. For per-allocation coverage of arena contents,
    callers must use the owned-heap allocator instead.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Allocate arena structure (24 bytes)
    Let arena be proc allocate with 24
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Failed to allocate arena structure
    End If

    Note: Allocate buffer using mmap for large allocations
    Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE = 3
    Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS = 0x22
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34  Note: 0x22
    Let buffer be proc syscall_mmap with 0, initial_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    Note: Check for mmap failure (returns -1 or negative)
    If buffer is less than 0:
        proc deallocate with arena
        Return 0  Note: Failed to allocate buffer
    End If

    Note: Initialize arena fields. used starts at 16 with DEBUG=1
    Note: so the leading 16 bytes are reserved for the arena
    Note: canary. With DEBUG=0 used starts at 0 (original behavior).
    Let initial_used be 0
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set initial_used to 16
        Note: Stamp leading canary. arena address is used as the
        Note: per-arena id; generation is 0 since arenas are not
        Note: reused at the same address by this allocator.
        proc canary_write_redzone with buffer, arena, 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_pointer with arena, 0, buffer      Note: buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 8, initial_size  Note: size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, initial_used Note: used

    Return arena
End Process

Process called "arena_allocate" takes arena as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate memory from arena (bump-pointer allocation)
    Note: Returns pointer to allocated memory, or 0 if out of space

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Invalid arena
    End If

    Note: Align allocation size to 8 bytes
    Let aligned_size be proc align_up with size, 8

    Note: Get current state
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_pointer with arena, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 8
    Let used be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 16

    Note: Check if we have enough space
    Let new_used be used plus aligned_size
    If new_used is greater than capacity:
        Return 0  Note: Out of arena space
    End If

    Note: Calculate allocation address
    Let ptr be buffer plus used

    Note: Update used counter (bump the pointer)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, new_used

    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "arena_string_duplicate" takes arena as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Duplicate string into arena memory
    Note: Used for temporary strings during compilation

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let len be proc string_length with str
    Let size be len plus 1  Note: Include null terminator

    Let new_str be proc arena_allocate with arena, size
    If new_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Arena out of space
    End If

    proc memory_copy with new_str, str, size
    Return new_str
End Process

Process called "arena_integer_to_string" takes arena as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert integer to string using arena
    Note: Eliminates temporary string leaks

    Note: Use heap version first, then copy to arena
    Let heap_str be proc integer_to_string with value
    Let arena_str be proc arena_string_duplicate with arena, heap_str
    proc deallocate with heap_str

    Return arena_str
End Process

Process called "arena_string_concat" takes arena as Integer, str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Concatenate strings using arena
    Note: Eliminates result leak

    Let heap_result be proc string_concat with str1, str2
    Let arena_result be proc arena_string_duplicate with arena, heap_result
    proc deallocate with heap_result

    Return arena_result
End Process

Process called "arena_reset" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resets the arena's bump pointer so the buffer can be reused.
    All allocations previously returned by arena_allocate become
    INVALID after this call - callers must not retain pointers
    into the arena across a reset.

    With DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED=1, before resetting we
    verify the leading canary (at buffer offset 0) and abort the
    process on mismatch. The reset target is "used = 16" so the
    bump pointer points just past the canary; with DEBUG=0 the
    target is "used = 0" (B2 behavior).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. If DEBUG=1: read buffer pointer, verify canary at offset 0
       using arena address as the id. Abort on mismatch.
    3. Reset used to (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    DEBUG=0 identical to pre-C5. DEBUG=1 adds one canary verify
    per reset (~12 ns). Reset is cold (called once per
    compilation pass or similar) so cost is irrelevant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Canary verify before reset is a NEW correctness boundary;
    detects leading-edge corruption that would silently survive a
    naked reset.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Let buffer_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with arena, 0
        If buffer_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let arena_canary_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with buffer_ptr, arena, 0
            If arena_canary_ok is equal to 0:
                Let arena_exp be proc canary_seed_word_a with arena, 0
                Let arena_got be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with buffer_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED, arena, 0, arena_exp, arena_got, buffer_ptr, arena
            End If
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, 16  Note: Reset used past canary
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arena, 16, 0  Note: Reset used to 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "arena_destroy" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Destroys the arena and reclaims its buffer in one bulk
    munmap. With DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED=1 we verify the
    arena's leading canary before munmap to detect catastrophic
    arena-buffer corruption. The canary mismatch aborts via
    canary_fail_abort.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Read buffer pointer and size from the arena struct.
    3. If DEBUG=1: verify canary at buffer offset 0 using
       arena address as id. Abort on mismatch.
    4. munmap(buffer, size).
    5. deallocate(arena) - frees the arena struct itself, which
       goes through the canary-protected owned-heap path.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path. DEBUG=1 adds ~12 ns canary verify before the
    O(1) munmap. Negligible.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Canary verify before munmap is a correctness boundary:
    detects buffer-start corruption before it gets fed silently
    into the unmap. Internal arena allocations remain unprotected
    by design (see arena_create @Security_Scope).
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc memory_get_pointer with arena, 0
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 8

    Note: Verify the arena's leading canary (DEBUG=1 only).
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        If buffer is not equal to 0:
            Let arena_canary_ok2 be proc canary_verify_redzone with buffer, arena, 0
            If arena_canary_ok2 is equal to 0:
                Let arena_exp2 be proc canary_seed_word_a with arena, 0
                Let arena_got2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with buffer, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED, arena, 0, arena_exp2, arena_got2, buffer, arena
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Unmap the buffer
    If buffer is not equal to 0:
        proc syscall_munmap with buffer, size
    End If

    Note: Free arena structure
    proc deallocate with arena

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "arena_get_used" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get bytes currently used in arena
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 16
End Process

Process called "arena_get_capacity" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get total capacity of arena
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arena, 8
End Process

Note: 
============================================================================
TIER 3: OWNED HEAP (Permanent Allocations)
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
Owned-heap allocation header (32 bytes, prepended to every owned
allocation, present at ptr - 32 where ptr is the user-data pointer
returned by allocate()):
  offset -32: allocation_id (unique id assigned via registry_allocate_id, 8 bytes)
  offset -24: generation     (incremented on reuse for use-after-free detection, 8 bytes)
  offset -16: total_size     (header + aligned_user_size, 8 bytes)
  offset -8:  alloc_type     (1=brk, 2=mmap, 8 bytes)
  offset 0:   user data begins here
deallocate() must read these offsets back exactly as allocate() wrote
them; the offset constants in both routines are a single source of
truth and changing one without the other corrupts every owned-heap
free in the system.
:End Note

Note:
Free List Structure (for brk-backed allocations):
When a brk block is freed via deallocate(), we reuse its user data area
to store free-list bookkeeping:
  offset 0: next_free (pointer to next free block in LIFO list, 8 bytes)
  offset 8: is_free   (1=free, 0=allocated, 8 bytes)
The 32-byte allocation header at offset -32..-1 remains intact with its
allocation_id, generation, size, and type values, so registry lookups
for borrows still resolve correctly while the block is parked on the
free list.
:End Note

Note: 
Free List Head (stored in heap metadata):
We reserve the first 16 bytes of the heap for metadata
offset 0: free_list_head (pointer to first free block)
offset 8: heap_initialized (1 if initialized, 0 otherwise)
:End Note

Let heap_metadata_addr be 0  Note: Will be initialized on first brk call

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Free List Management Functions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "heap_init" returns Integer:
    Note: Initialize heap metadata on first brk allocation
    Note: Reserves 16 bytes at the start of the heap for free list metadata

    If heap_metadata_addr is not equal to 0:
        Return heap_metadata_addr  Note: Already initialized
    End If

    Note: Get current brk (this will be our metadata location)
    Let current_brk be proc syscall_brk with 0
    Set heap_metadata_addr to current_brk

    Note: Reserve 16 bytes for metadata
    Let metadata_size be 16
    Let new_brk be current_brk plus metadata_size
    Let result_brk be proc syscall_brk with new_brk

    If result_brk is less than new_brk:
        Set heap_metadata_addr to 0
        Return 0  Note: Failed to reserve metadata space
    End If

    Note: Initialize metadata
    proc memory_set_pointer with heap_metadata_addr, 0, 0  Note: free_list_head = NULL
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with heap_metadata_addr, 8, 1     Note: heap_initialized = 1

    Note: Seed the owned-heap bounding box with the initial brk reservation
    Note: so subsequent deallocate calls on pointers within the heap-metadata
    Note: region (none expected, but defensive) survive the range guard. The
    Note: span [heap_metadata_addr, new_brk) covers exactly the 16 bytes we
    Note: just reserved; later allocate() calls will extend it.
    Let heap_init_track_ok be proc owned_range_extend with heap_metadata_addr, new_brk

    Return heap_metadata_addr
End Process

Process called "heap_get_free_list_head" returns Integer:
    Note: Get pointer to the first free block
    If heap_metadata_addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_pointer with heap_metadata_addr, 0
End Process

Process called "heap_set_free_list_head" takes head as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set the free list head pointer
    If heap_metadata_addr is equal to 0:
        Let dummy be proc heap_init
    End If
    proc memory_set_pointer with heap_metadata_addr, 0, head
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_list_find_fit" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find a free block that fits the requested size (first-fit algorithm)
    Note: Returns pointer to user data area, or 0 if no fit found

    Let current be proc heap_get_free_list_head

    While current is not equal to 0:
        Let block_size be proc free_block_get_size with current
        If block_size is greater than or equal to size:
            Return current  Note: Found a fit
        End If
        Set current to proc free_block_get_next with current
    End While

    Return 0  Note: No suitable block found
End Process

Process called "free_list_remove_block" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Remove block from free list (when reusing it for allocation)

    Let head be proc heap_get_free_list_head
    Let next be 0  Note: Declare once at function scope

    Note: If it's the head, update head pointer
    If block is equal to head:
        Set next to proc free_block_get_next with block
        Let dummy be proc heap_set_free_list_head with next
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Search for block in the list
    Let current be head
    While current is not equal to 0:
        Set next to proc free_block_get_next with current
        If next is equal to block:
            Note: Found it - unlink from list
            Let next_next be proc free_block_get_next with block
            Let dummy2 be proc free_block_set_next with current, next_next
            Return 1
        End If
        Set current to next
    End While

    Return 0  Note: Block not found in list
End Process

Process called "free_list_add_block" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add block to the front of free list (LIFO)

    Let old_head be proc heap_get_free_list_head
    Let dummy be proc free_block_set_next with block, old_head
    Let dummy2 be proc free_block_set_free_flag with block, 1
    Let dummy3 be proc heap_set_free_list_head with block
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_block_set_next" takes block as Integer, next as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set next pointer in a free block (block points to user data area)
    proc memory_set_pointer with block, 0, next
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_block_get_next" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next pointer from a free block
    Return proc memory_get_pointer with block, 0
End Process

Process called "free_block_set_free_flag" takes block as Integer, is_free as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Mark block as free (1) or allocated (0)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with block, 8, is_free
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_block_get_free_flag" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if block is free
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with block, 8
End Process

Process called "free_block_get_size" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the total_size field (header + aligned user bytes) for a
    block that is currently parked on the brk free list. The block
    pointer is the user-data address - the same pointer that allocate()
    handed out before the block was freed - so the size field lives at
    block - header_size + 16 in absolute terms. The header is 32 bytes
    when DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is 0 (B2 invariant) or 48
    bytes when DEBUG is 1 (canonical 32-byte block + 16-byte pre-canary).
    This routine resolves header_size at runtime so it matches the
    DEBUG-aware layouts used by allocate() and deallocate(). total_size
    at offset 16 of the header is the full block size INCLUDING
    header AND post-canary; callers that need just the user-bytes
    capacity must subtract header_size + (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Resolve header_size = 32 + (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    2. Subtract header_size from the user-data pointer to get
       header_ptr.
    3. Read total_size at offset 16 of the header.
    @End Implementation

    Let header_size be ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let header_ptr be block minus header_size
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CANARY / QUARANTINE HELPERS (ASan-class protocol)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "canary_seed_word_a" takes alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Derives the first per-allocation canary word from (alloc_id, generation).
    Uses a SplitMix64-style mix: multiply by an odd 64-bit constant, XOR
    with another constant, multiply again. The output has good avalanche
    properties across consecutive allocation_ids so canaries for
    neighboring allocations look uncorrelated. An attacker who reads ONE
    freed block's canary cannot predict the canary of another block
    without also knowing its allocation_id+generation, which lives in
    the registry, not in user-controllable memory.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Steps:
     1. Compute mixed = alloc_id * CANARY_SEED_MULT_A.
     2. XOR with generation.
     3. XOR with CANARY_SEED_XOR_A.
     4. Multiply by CANARY_SEED_MULT_B and return.
    All arithmetic is 64-bit signed in Runa; overflow is the normal
    mixing behavior we want and is well-defined wraparound on x86_64.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three integer multiplies and two XORs. Approximately 4 ns on a
    modern x86_64 core. Called twice per allocate/deallocate (pre +
    post canary). With DEBUG=0 the canary call sites are guarded so
    this routine is never invoked in release builds.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The canary is NOT a cryptographic MAC - an attacker who can read
    process memory can recover both seed multipliers and forge the
    canary for any (alloc_id, generation) pair. The protection is
    against UNINTENTIONAL corruption (buffer overrun, use-after-free
    that writes the wrong bytes), not against a memory-disclosure
    adversary. For that, escalate to a process-startup-random seed
    XOR'd in - left as a v0.0.9.x hardening pass.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mixed be alloc_id multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_A
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor generation
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor CANARY_SEED_XOR_A
    Set mixed to mixed multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_B
    Return mixed
End Process

Process called "canary_seed_word_b" takes alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Derives the second per-allocation canary word from (alloc_id, generation).
    Uses different mix constants from canary_seed_word_a so the two
    words in a 16-byte canary pair are independent: corrupting both
    requires guessing two 64-bit values, not one.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Same SplitMix64-style mix as canary_seed_word_a but with arguments
    swapped (generation first, then alloc_id) and the CANARY_SEED_XOR_B
    constant instead of A. The asymmetry guarantees word_a != word_b for
    every allocation.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost profile as canary_seed_word_a. DEBUG=0 elides via guard.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same as canary_seed_word_a: best-effort against unintentional
    corruption; not a cryptographic boundary.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mixed be generation multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_A
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor alloc_id
    Set mixed to mixed bitwise xor CANARY_SEED_XOR_B
    Set mixed to mixed multiplied by CANARY_SEED_MULT_B
    Return mixed
End Process

Process called "canary_write_redzone" takes redzone_ptr as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes the 16-byte canary pair (two 8-byte words) at redzone_ptr.
    Used for both the pre-buffer redzone (inside the expanded header at
    header_ptr + 32) and the post-buffer redzone (at ptr + aligned_size).
    The two words are derived from the same (alloc_id, generation)
    inputs so the pre and post canaries match - a corruption that
    happens to overwrite both pre and post identically (e.g., a wild
    memset) is still detectable because the corrupted bytes will not
    derive correctly from the registry-tracked allocation_id.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute word_a via canary_seed_word_a(alloc_id, generation).
    2. Compute word_b via canary_seed_word_b(alloc_id, generation).
    3. memory_set_int64(redzone_ptr, 0, word_a).
    4. memory_set_int64(redzone_ptr, 8, word_b).
    The caller is responsible for ensuring redzone_ptr points at 16
    bytes the allocator owns; passing a foreign pointer here corrupts
    16 bytes silently.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two integer mixes + two 64-bit stores. About 10 ns on a modern
    core. Called twice per allocate (pre + post). DEBUG=0 elides at
    call sites.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes 16 bytes at redzone_ptr. The caller must verify ownership;
    layout.runa always passes addresses inside its own brk/mmap'd
    regions, so misuse from external callers is structurally
    prevented (this Process is module-private in intent though not in
    visibility).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let word_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id, generation
    Let word_b be proc canary_seed_word_b with alloc_id, generation
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 0, word_a
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 8, word_b
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_verify_redzone" takes redzone_ptr as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Verifies the 16-byte canary at redzone_ptr matches the expected
    value derived from (alloc_id, generation). Returns 1 on match, 0 on
    mismatch. Callers that detect a mismatch should abort via
    canary_fail_abort (which writes a fixed-format diagnostic to
    stderr and exits 134, mirroring ASan).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Read stored_word_a at redzone_ptr+0.
    2. Read stored_word_b at redzone_ptr+8.
    3. Recompute expected_word_a, expected_word_b via the mix.
    4. Compare. If EITHER mismatches, return 0. Otherwise return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads + two mixes + two compares. ~12 ns. Called twice per
    deallocate (pre + post) and twice per brk-reuse allocate. DEBUG=0
    elides at call sites.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The verifier reads 16 bytes at redzone_ptr; the caller must
    guarantee those bytes are inside the allocator's owned regions.
    A successful verify proves the canary slot was not overwritten
    by a buffer overrun OR by a use-after-free write that happened to
    miss the slot - but does NOT prove the user buffer is uncorrupted
    (the middle of the buffer is not canary-protected, that requires
    shadow memory which is out of scope).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let stored_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 0
    Let stored_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with redzone_ptr, 8
    Let expected_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id, generation
    Let expected_b be proc canary_seed_word_b with alloc_id, generation
    If stored_a is not equal to expected_a:
        Return 0
    End If
    If stored_b is not equal to expected_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_poison_buffer" takes buffer_ptr as Integer, size_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Overwrites a freed user buffer with CANARY_POISON_WORD repeated. A
    pointer that survives across the free (use-after-free) and is read
    later as an Integer will return CANARY_POISON_WORD (0xDEADBEEFDEADBEEF),
    which is an obvious sentinel during debugging. Use-after-free
    writes through the dangling pointer are detected at the next
    canary verify if they happen to clobber the post-buffer canary;
    writes to the middle of the buffer are NOT detected here (that
    needs shadow memory). The poison is therefore a partial-protection
    layer that improves diagnosability without claiming completeness.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute word_count = size_bytes / 8 (truncating; the buffer is
       8-byte aligned by aligned_size logic).
    2. Loop i in [0, word_count): memory_set_int64(buffer_ptr, i*8,
       CANARY_POISON_WORD).
    Any trailing bytes (size_bytes mod 8) are not poisoned. In
    practice aligned_size is always a multiple of 8 so the tail is
    empty.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(size / 8) stores. For a 1024-byte allocation this is 128 stores
    ~= 80 ns. The cost scales with allocation size so we only do this
    in DEBUG=1. A vectorized memory_fill could halve the cost but is
    out of scope for v0.0.8.5.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes size_bytes at buffer_ptr. Caller must guarantee buffer_ptr
    is the user pointer of a block currently owned by the allocator
    and that size_bytes does not exceed aligned_size for that block.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size_bytes is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let word_count be size_bytes divided by 8
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than word_count:
        Let byte_offset be i multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer_ptr, byte_offset, CANARY_POISON_WORD
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_emit_hex_word" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits a 16-character lowercase hex representation of value to fd 2
    (stderr) followed by no separator. Used by canary_fail_abort to
    format the expected/got canary words in the diagnostic message.
    Inlined to one 18-byte stack buffer (16 hex + 2-char "0x" prefix)
    so the diagnostic does not allocate during a failure path.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate a 18-byte stack buffer via repeated memory_set_byte on
       a small mmap'd scratch region (we cannot use a true stack buffer
       in pure-Runa primitives; instead we pre-create a 32-byte
       mmap-backed scratch the first time and reuse it).
    2. Write the "0x" prefix.
    3. For i in [0, 16): extract the (15-i)th nibble of value (most
       significant nibble first), translate to ASCII hex character,
       store at buffer+2+i.
    4. syscall_write(fd=2, buf, 18).
    The scratch buffer is module-statically located via a Let; lazy
    init on first use. After the program crashes via syscall_exit,
    the scratch is reclaimed by the OS.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Failure-path only. Never on the hot path. Cost is irrelevant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes to a private 32-byte mmap'd region the allocator owns and
    to fd 2. No attacker-controlled paths.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let scratch be proc canary_get_diag_scratch
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 48   Note: '0'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 120  Note: 'x'
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let shift_amount be 15 minus i
        Set shift_amount to shift_amount multiplied by 4
        Let nibble be value shifted right by shift_amount
        Set nibble to nibble bitwise and 15
        Let char_code be 0
        If nibble is less than 10:
            Set char_code to nibble plus 48   Note: '0'..'9'
        Otherwise:
            Set char_code to nibble plus 87   Note: 'a'..'f' (97 - 10)
        End If
        Let byte_offset be i plus 2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, byte_offset, char_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 18
    Return 1
End Process

Let canary_diag_scratch_ptr be 0    Note: mmap-backed 32-byte scratch for hex formatting

Process called "canary_get_diag_scratch" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazy-initializes the 32-byte scratch buffer used by
    canary_emit_hex_word for failure diagnostics. Allocated via mmap
    directly (not through allocate) because the failure path must
    function even if the heap is corrupted.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    On first call: mmap a 32-byte page-aligned region with PROT_READ|
    PROT_WRITE | MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS, store the pointer, return
    it. On subsequent calls: return the cached pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path (only fires on canary failure). One-shot mmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates 32 bytes outside the regular heap registry. The region
    is never freed - it lives for the process lifetime. Acceptable
    since failure diagnostics are terminal.
    @End Security_Scope

    If canary_diag_scratch_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Return canary_diag_scratch_ptr
    End If
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 32, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set canary_diag_scratch_ptr to ptr
    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "canary_emit_literal" takes literal_ptr as Integer, literal_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a constant byte sequence to fd 2 via syscall_write. The
    "literal" must be a memory region the caller owns and has filled
    with bytes ahead of time. Used to emit the fixed prefix of the
    canary failure diagnostic.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single syscall_write(2, literal_ptr, literal_len).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Failure-path only.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes literal_len bytes to fd 2. Caller-supplied region; caller
    is responsible for the bytes.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, literal_ptr, literal_len
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "canary_fail_abort" takes location_code as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, generation as Integer, expected_word_a as Integer, got_word_a as Integer, header_ptr as Integer, user_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Terminal failure handler for canary mismatches. Writes a
    fixed-format diagnostic to stderr (fd 2) and exits with code 134
    (= 128 + SIGABRT, mirrors how libc abort() terminates and matches
    AddressSanitizer's exit convention). Never returns.

    The diagnostic format is:
        CANARY FAILURE loc=N id=N gen=N exp=0x.. got=0x.. hdr=0x.. usr=0x..
    All values are emitted as 16-char hex (alloc_id, generation,
    expected, got, header_ptr, user_ptr) or single-digit ASCII for
    location_code. The format is fixed so external tooling can parse
    it without ambiguity.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate a small mmap'd "literal" region the first time (32
       bytes); reused via the canary_diag_scratch_ptr from
       canary_get_diag_scratch.
    2. Emit each literal segment via syscall_write inline (we manually
       build short byte sequences in-place to avoid needing a string
       table).
    3. Emit each hex value via canary_emit_hex_word.
    4. syscall_exit(134) - process terminates.

    Implementation uses repeated memory_set_byte to build the literal
    segments because pure-Runa primitives don't expose string-literal
    pointers to bytes; each segment is written byte-by-byte and then
    syscall_write'd.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Terminal path. Cost is irrelevant. Designed to be minimal-LOC
    rather than minimal-cycle.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes attacker-readable bytes (alloc_id, generation, expected
    canary, observed canary, header pointer, user pointer) to fd 2.
    If stderr is attacker-readable this leaks the canary seed
    derivation evidence. Acceptable: at this point the process is
    already known to have been corrupted and will exit; the goal is
    diagnosability, not confidentiality.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let scratch be proc canary_get_diag_scratch
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Note: Cannot allocate scratch - direct exit, no diagnostic possible.
        proc syscall_exit from Syscall with 134
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Emit "CANARY FAILURE loc=" (19 bytes).
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 67    Note: 'C'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 65    Note: 'A'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 78    Note: 'N'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 65    Note: 'A'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 82    Note: 'R'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 5, 89    Note: 'Y'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 6, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 7, 70    Note: 'F'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 8, 65    Note: 'A'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 9, 73    Note: 'I'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 10, 76   Note: 'L'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 11, 85   Note: 'U'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 12, 82   Note: 'R'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 13, 69   Note: 'E'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 14, 32   Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 15, 108  Note: 'l'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 16, 111  Note: 'o'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 17, 99   Note: 'c'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 18, 61   Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 19

    Note: Emit location_code as a single ASCII digit (we have 5 codes; all single digit).
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, location_code plus 48
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 1

    Note: Emit " id=" prefix and the allocation id in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 105   Note: 'i'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 100   Note: 'd'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 4
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with alloc_id

    Note: Emit " gen=" prefix and generation in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 103   Note: 'g'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 101   Note: 'e'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 110   Note: 'n'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with generation

    Note: Emit " exp=" prefix and expected_word_a in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 101   Note: 'e'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 120   Note: 'x'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 112   Note: 'p'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with expected_word_a

    Note: Emit " got=" prefix and got_word_a in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 103   Note: 'g'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 111   Note: 'o'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 116   Note: 't'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with got_word_a

    Note: Emit " hdr=" prefix and header_ptr in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 104   Note: 'h'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 100   Note: 'd'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 114   Note: 'r'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with header_ptr

    Note: Emit " usr=" prefix and user_ptr in hex.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 32    Note: ' '
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 1, 117   Note: 'u'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 2, 115   Note: 's'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 3, 114   Note: 'r'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 4, 61    Note: '='
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 5
    proc canary_emit_hex_word with user_ptr

    Note: Emit trailing newline.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with scratch, 0, 10    Note: '\n'
    proc syscall_write from Syscall with 2, scratch, 1

    Note: Terminate process. Exit code 134 = 128 + SIGABRT, matching ASan.
    proc syscall_exit from Syscall with 134
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "quarantine_init" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazily allocates the quarantine ring buffer the first time
    deallocate runs with DEBUG=1. The quarantine stores
    QUARANTINE_CAPACITY entries of QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE bytes each,
    backed by a single mmap region so the quarantine itself never
    competes with the heap registry.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Check quarantine_initialized; if 1, return 1. Otherwise mmap
    (QUARANTINE_CAPACITY * QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE) bytes with
    PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE | MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, zero-fill,
    store the pointer, mark initialized.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One-shot per program lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates 2048 bytes outside the regular heap registry. The
    region is freed at program exit only.
    @End Security_Scope

    If quarantine_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let total_size be QUARANTINE_CAPACITY multiplied by QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let table_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If table_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with table_ptr, 0, total_size
    Set quarantine_table to table_ptr
    Set quarantine_head to 0
    Set quarantine_count to 0
    Set quarantine_initialized to 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "quarantine_push" takes user_ptr as Integer, total_size as Integer, alloc_id as Integer, alloc_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pushes a freshly-freed block onto the quarantine ring buffer.
    Returns the evicted entry's user_ptr (or 0 if no eviction
    happened yet). The caller is responsible for ACTUALLY freeing
    the evicted entry (munmap for mmap allocations, free-list-add
    for brk). This split lets deallocate keep its tier-specific
    finalization logic in deallocate itself; quarantine_push is a
    pure data-structure operation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Entry layout (32 bytes):
       offset  0 -> user_ptr      (8 bytes)
       offset  8 -> total_size    (8 bytes)
       offset 16 -> alloc_id      (8 bytes)
       offset 24 -> alloc_type    (8 bytes)

    Steps:
     1. Ensure quarantine_init has run.
     2. Compute slot_ptr = quarantine_table + quarantine_head * 32.
     3. If quarantine_count == QUARANTINE_CAPACITY: read the OLD
        entry's user_ptr/total_size/alloc_id/alloc_type into out
        params and return user_ptr-of-old; we are EVICTING the slot.
     4. Otherwise return 0 (no eviction yet).
     5. Write the new entry at slot_ptr.
     6. quarantine_head = (quarantine_head + 1) mod QUARANTINE_CAPACITY.
     7. quarantine_count = min(quarantine_count + 1, QUARANTINE_CAPACITY).

    Since Runa primitives don't support out-params, we return only
    the evicted user_ptr; the eviction's total_size, alloc_id, and
    alloc_type are looked up via quarantine_get_evicted_*-style
    helpers OR cached in module-level slots written by this
    Process. Chosen approach: cache via module-level Let slots
    quarantine_last_evicted_total_size / _alloc_id / _alloc_type
    so the caller reads them right after quarantine_push returns
    nonzero. This avoids needing multi-return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) - one indexed write, three pointer updates. ~10 ns per
    push. The eviction case adds three more reads = ~14 ns.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must verify user_ptr is currently owned by the allocator
    and has its canaries intact at the time of push. Quarantine
    does NOT re-verify on push; verification happens at eviction
    time inside quarantine_pop_evict_for_reuse.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let init_ok be proc quarantine_init
    If init_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head_offset be quarantine_head multiplied by QUARANTINE_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let slot_ptr be quarantine_table plus head_offset
    Let evicted_user_ptr be 0
    If quarantine_count is greater than or equal to QUARANTINE_CAPACITY:
        Set evicted_user_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 0
        Let evicted_total_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 8
        Let evicted_alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 16
        Let evicted_alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 24
        Set quarantine_last_evicted_total_size to evicted_total_size
        Set quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_id to evicted_alloc_id
        Set quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_type to evicted_alloc_type
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 0, user_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 8, total_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 16, alloc_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot_ptr, 24, alloc_type
    Set quarantine_head to quarantine_head plus 1
    If quarantine_head is greater than or equal to QUARANTINE_CAPACITY:
        Set quarantine_head to 0
    End If
    If quarantine_count is less than QUARANTINE_CAPACITY:
        Set quarantine_count to quarantine_count plus 1
    End If
    Return evicted_user_ptr
End Process

Let quarantine_last_evicted_total_size be 0
Let quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_id be 0
Let quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_type be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: E3 SIZE-CLASS POOL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "pool_class_for_size" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Maps an 8-byte-aligned allocation size to a pool size-class index in 0..19.
    The size table is implicit in this compare cascade: classes 0..7 step by 8
    (8, 16, 24, 32, 40, 48, 56, 64), classes 8..11 step by 16 (80, 96, 112, 128),
    classes 12..15 step by 32 (160, 192, 224, 256), classes 16..19 step by 64
    (320, 384, 448, 512). For size > 512 returns -1 to signal "fall through to
    brk/mmap." The cascade is sequential by design so the branch predictor learns
    the common cases (~ <= 64 byte allocations are the parser AST node hot path).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four-branch piecewise arithmetic. Each tier (steps 8, 16, 32, 64) maps a
    sub-range to its class index via subtract-and-shift. Beats both a 20-way
    If-cascade (compile-time bloat, runtime branch count) and a 65-entry side
    table LUT (cache pressure, indirection). Fixed ~4-6 instructions hot path
    on any platform.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Branchless within each tier (subtract + shift). Worst case 4 compares for
    size > 512 returning -1. Hot path (sizes <= 64 bytes, the parser AST node
    range) takes a single branch and one shift. Compile-friendly: shrinks
    the function from ~60 lines of If-cascade to ~10 lines of arithmetic,
    which materially cuts codegen time for layout.runa.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No memory access. Input size is bounded by caller (allocate guards against
    negative sizes and the POOL_MAX_SIZE check happens at the call site).
    Negative or zero sizes route to class 0 (8-byte slot) via the floor of
    the (size - 1) >> 3 expression at size = 1.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If size is less than or equal to 64:
        Return (size minus 1) divided by 8
    End If
    If size is less than or equal to 128:
        Return 8 plus ((size minus 65) divided by 16)
    End If
    If size is less than or equal to 256:
        Return 12 plus ((size minus 129) divided by 32)
    End If
    If size is less than or equal to 512:
        Return 16 plus ((size minus 257) divided by 64)
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "pool_size_for_class" takes class_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of pool_class_for_size. Used by pool_slab_new to compute the slot
    size when carving a fresh slab. Compare cascade by class index, mirroring
    the size-class table documented at the head of the E3 subsystem.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four-branch piecewise arithmetic, mirroring pool_class_for_size. Each tier
    of the size table is reconstructed via add-and-shift on the class index.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold-ish path (called once per slab allocation, i.e., once per ~thousands
    of pool_alloc calls), so arithmetic vs LUT is performance-neutral here.
    Chosen for symmetry with pool_class_for_size and for compile-time savings:
    the cascade form added ~60 lines that materially slowed codegen of
    layout.runa.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; no memory access. Out-of-range class_idx (< 0 or >= 20)
    returns 0 to signal "no valid size class," matching the cascade's
    fall-through behavior.
    @End Security_Scope

    If class_idx is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If class_idx is less than 8:
        Return (class_idx plus 1) multiplied by 8
    End If
    If class_idx is less than 12:
        Return 64 plus ((class_idx minus 7) multiplied by 16)
    End If
    If class_idx is less than 16:
        Return 128 plus ((class_idx minus 11) multiplied by 32)
    End If
    If class_idx is less than 20:
        Return 256 plus ((class_idx minus 15) multiplied by 64)
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "pool_init" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazily allocates the 640-byte pool state table on the first pool_alloc call.
    The table holds POOL_NUM_CLASSES (20) entries of POOL_STATE_ENTRY_SIZE
    (32) bytes each. Allocated via mmap so the allocator does not bootstrap-
    depend on itself.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Idempotent: if pool_initialized is already 1, return 1. Otherwise mmap
    POOL_STATE_TABLE_SIZE bytes PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE | MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS,
    zero-fill, store the pointer in pool_state_table, set pool_initialized to 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One-shot per process lifetime. Subsequent pool_alloc calls skip this via
    the pool_initialized check (one branch, ~1 ns).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates 640 bytes outside the regular allocator. The region lives for
    the process lifetime; OS reclaims on exit.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let table_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, POOL_STATE_TABLE_SIZE, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If table_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with table_ptr, 0, POOL_STATE_TABLE_SIZE
    Set pool_state_table to table_ptr
    Set pool_initialized to 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "pool_state_entry_ptr" takes class_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the address of the 32-byte per-class state entry within
    pool_state_table. The entry layout is freelist_head@0, slab_chain_head@8,
    bump_pointer@16, bump_limit@24. Callers index this address with the
    canonical offsets to read or update fields.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    pool_state_table + class_idx * POOL_STATE_ENTRY_SIZE. Caller is
    responsible for having called pool_init first.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One multiply + one add. ~1 ns. Inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must ensure class_idx is in [0, POOL_NUM_CLASSES). The pool fast
    path validates this via pool_class_for_size's bounded return.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let offset be class_idx multiplied by POOL_STATE_ENTRY_SIZE
    Return pool_state_table plus offset
End Process

Process called "pool_slab_base_of" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Recovers the slab base address from any pointer by consulting the
    authoritative slab_registry rather than masking ptr to a 64 KiB
    boundary. The bitmask approach (ptr & POOL_SLAB_BASE_MASK) was
    UNSAFE: it assumed pool slabs are 64 KiB-aligned, but syscall_mmap
    returns kernel-page-aligned memory (typically 4 KiB on x86-64), so
    the rounded-down "base" can be numerically below the genuine slab
    base. A subsequent header read at that wrong base lands in an
    unmapped or unrelated page and SEGVs the process. The registry
    lookup returns the ACTUAL base recorded by pool_slab_new at insert
    time, so the result is correct regardless of the alignment the
    kernel chose for the underlying mmap.

    Returns 0 when ptr is not contained in any registered pool slab
    (NULL pointer, pointer outside the pool address range, registry
    not yet initialized, or pointer in a gap between registered slabs).
    Callers may still treat the returned base as authoritative for
    pool-slot recovery; the optional signature read at offset 0 remains
    as a defense-in-depth check against future code paths that might
    mis-register or stale-register a slab.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to slab_registry_base_of, which performs an O(log N)
    binary search over the sorted slab-base array (pre-filtered by the
    pool_slab_addr_min / pool_slab_addr_max bounding box). Returns 0
    for ptr = 0 indirectly through the same delegate's NULL guard.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pre-filter rejects in ~1 ns; registry survivors complete in ~10-15
    ns for a full 4096-entry registry. Replaces the prior single-AND
    one-cycle implementation; the increase is intentional and bounded,
    and is required for correctness (the prior implementation could
    return a wrong base that SEGV'd on subsequent dereference).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns either a genuine slab base recorded by pool_slab_new (a
    fully mapped, allocator-owned address) or 0; the returned value is
    therefore always safe to dereference at offset 0 when non-zero,
    because the registry only contains bases of slabs that have been
    successfully mmap'd. Never dereferences ptr.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc slab_registry_base_of with ptr
End Process

Process called "slab_registry_init" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazy first-touch initialization of the slab-base registry. Allocates
    SLAB_REGISTRY_TOTAL_SIZE bytes (32 KiB, exactly 8 pages on a 4 KiB
    page) via syscall_mmap with PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE |
    MAP_ANONYMOUS, fd=-1, offset=0. The mapped region is zero-filled by
    the kernel which gives slab_registry_count an implicit starting value
    of zero entries.

    Idempotent: returns immediately if slab_registry_initialized is
    already 1. This allows slab_registry_insert to call init on every
    invocation without measurable overhead after first-touch.

    The registry is mmap'd directly via syscall, NOT through allocate.
    It must not depend on the very allocator whose deallocate fast path
    it gates -- a self-reference would deadlock or recurse infinitely.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If slab_registry_initialized is 1, return 1.
    2. syscall_mmap(0, 32768, PROT=3, MAP_PRIVATE|ANONYMOUS=34, -1, 0).
    3. If the syscall returned a negative value, mmap failed; return 0.
    4. Store the address in slab_registry, set slab_registry_initialized
       to 1, and return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Called once per process lifetime in the successful case. After the
    first invocation the early-exit branch is ~1 ns. mmap itself is
    ~5 us, amortized to negligible across thousands of allocations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates 32 KiB of anonymous private memory readable and writable
    by the current process. No attacker-controlled byte enters the
    mmap arguments. Returning 0 on mmap failure is the only failure
    mode; the caller (slab_registry_insert) treats this as a hard
    allocator failure.
    @End Security_Scope

    If slab_registry_initialized is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let region be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, SLAB_REGISTRY_TOTAL_SIZE, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If region is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set slab_registry to region
    Set slab_registry_capacity to SLAB_REGISTRY_CAPACITY
    Set slab_registry_initialized to 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "slab_registry_grow" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Doubles the slab registry backing array via mmap+memory_copy+munmap.
    Invoked by slab_registry_insert when slab_registry_count has reached
    slab_registry_capacity, BEFORE the binary search and shift logic so
    that from the caller's perspective the insert is atomic: either the
    array has room and the insert proceeds, or grow failed (OOM) and
    insert returns 0 without mutating registry state.

    Geometric doubling (4096 -> 8192 -> 16384 -> ...) is the classic
    pattern used by every production allocator (mimalloc, jemalloc,
    tcmalloc, glibc malloc) when its internal bookkeeping fills up. It
    gives amortized O(1) per insert and an exponentially shrinking grow
    frequency. There is no hard upper bound on capacity; the only
    ceiling is the kernel mmap budget. On OOM grow returns 0, insert
    returns 0, pool_slab_new munmaps the just-installed slab, allocate
    falls back to brk -- the allocator degrades gracefully under
    exhaustion. It never crashes.

    Pointer-then-capacity swap order: the new pointer is published
    before the new capacity is published, and the old array is
    munmapped AFTER both publishes. For single-threaded v0.0.8.5 the
    ordering is irrelevant (insert and contains never overlap on a
    single thread), but it is the correct safe-default sequence for
    the v0.0.9.x RCU upgrade path. A reader that loaded the old
    pointer would see "old pointer with old capacity"; one that loaded
    the new pointer would see "new pointer with capacity at least old
    capacity"; neither combination can index past the end of its
    observed buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute new_capacity = slab_registry_capacity * 2.
    2. Compute new_size_bytes = new_capacity * SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE.
    3. syscall_mmap(0, new_size_bytes, PROT_READ|WRITE=3,
       MAP_PRIVATE|ANONYMOUS=34, -1, 0). On a negative return value,
       mmap failed: return 0 and leave the registry untouched.
    4. memory_copy(new_table, old_table, slab_registry_count *
       SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE). Only the live prefix is copied; the
       remaining new entries are kernel-zeroed.
    5. Capture saved_old_table and saved_old_size, then publish:
       slab_registry := new_table; slab_registry_capacity := new_capacity.
    6. syscall_munmap(saved_old_table, saved_old_size). On modern Linux
       munmap of an mmap'd region cannot fail for an aligned process-
       owned region; the return value is not checked.
    7. Return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path. Frequency falls exponentially: 0 grows on workloads
    below 4096 live slabs, 1 grow at 4097, 2 at 8193, etc. Cost per
    grow is one syscall_mmap + one memory_copy (32 KiB doubling to 64
    KiB at the first grow) + one syscall_munmap, on the order of
    10-20 us total. Amortized cost per insert is O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocates anonymous private memory readable and writable by the
    current process and copies the existing sorted entries into it.
    The destination is freshly mapped (kernel-zeroed beyond the copied
    prefix). No attacker-controlled byte enters the mmap arguments or
    the copy length. The old mapping is unmapped immediately, returning
    its pages to the kernel.

    MULTI-THREAD FUTURE WORK: When v0.0.9.x introduces per-thread pools
    this grow path will require either (a) an exclusive writer / shared
    reader lock around init/insert/grow/contains, or (b) RCU / seqlock
    with epoch-based old-array reclamation, or (c) per-thread registries
    with merge-on-collection. The current pointer-then-capacity swap
    order is the safe-default for option (b).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let old_capacity be slab_registry_capacity
    Let new_capacity be old_capacity multiplied by 2
    Let new_size_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let new_table be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, new_size_bytes, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If new_table is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let old_table be slab_registry
    Let live_bytes be slab_registry_count multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    If live_bytes is greater than 0:
        proc memory_copy with new_table, old_table, live_bytes
    End If
    Let saved_old_table be old_table
    Let saved_old_size be old_capacity multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Set slab_registry to new_table
    Set slab_registry_capacity to new_capacity
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with saved_old_table, saved_old_size
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "slab_registry_insert" takes slab_base as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Registers a freshly-allocated slab in the sorted slab-base registry.
    Called exactly once per slab by pool_slab_new, before any user
    pointer derived from the slab can reach deallocate. Maintains the
    registry's sorted-ascending invariant via upper-bound binary search
    + top-down shift-right.

    Also updates the pool_slab_addr_min / pool_slab_addr_max bounding-
    box pair. min is the lowest registered slab base, max is the
    highest registered slab base plus POOL_SLAB_SIZE (one past the last
    payload byte). The pair is a cheap pre-filter ahead of the binary
    search in slab_registry_contains; it admits some false positives
    (pointers numerically in the range but in gaps between slabs), but
    those are caught by the binary search.

    Overflow (count == slab_registry_capacity) triggers a dynamic
    resize: slab_registry_grow doubles the backing array via fresh
    mmap + memory_copy + munmap before the binary search proceeds. On
    grow failure (OOM) insert returns 0 without mutating registry
    state, and the caller (pool_slab_new) treats a non-1 return as
    "registry unavailable, undo the slab mmap and propagate failure".
    From the caller's perspective the insert is atomic: either count
    is incremented and the entry is in place, or 0 is returned and
    nothing changed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Lazy init via slab_registry_init. If init fails, return 0.
    2. Reject NULL or negative slab_base defensively.
    3. If count is at or above slab_registry_capacity, call
       slab_registry_grow. On grow failure (OOM), return 0.
    4. Upper-bound binary search: find lowest index i in [0, count]
       such that registry[i] > slab_base. Invariant: every entry at
       index < lo is <= slab_base; every entry at index >= hi is >
       slab_base. On loop exit lo == hi == i, the insertion point.
    5. Top-down shift: for j from count down to i+1, copy
       registry[j-1] into registry[j]. Reading j-1 before writing
       j-1 preserves correctness because each iteration writes a
       slot whose previous value has already been read.
    6. Write slab_base at registry[i].
    7. Increment count.
    8. Update pool_slab_addr_min and pool_slab_addr_max from the
       new sorted endpoints.
    9. Return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path -- called once per slab creation, amortized across
    thousands of pool allocations per slab. Binary search is O(log
    count); shift cost is O(count - i). The grow check is a single
    compare in the common case; the grow body itself fires at
    exponentially shrinking frequency (zero grows under 4096 live
    slabs, then once each doubling).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Reads and writes the slab_registry region (mmap'd private memory
    owned by this process). slab_base is supplied by pool_slab_new
    immediately after syscall_mmap; only this allocator writes to the
    registry. No attacker-controlled byte determines a registry
    index or stored value. slab_registry_capacity is the only state
    that the grow path mutates outside of the registry buffer itself.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let init_ok be proc slab_registry_init
    If init_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_base is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_registry_count is greater than or equal to slab_registry_capacity:
        Let grow_ok be proc slab_registry_grow
        If grow_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be slab_registry_count
    While lo is less than hi:
        Let mid be lo plus hi
        Set mid to mid divided by 2
        Let mid_offset be mid multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let mid_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, mid_offset
        If mid_base is greater than slab_base:
            Set hi to mid
        Otherwise:
            Set lo to mid plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let insert_index be lo

    Let j be slab_registry_count
    While j is greater than insert_index:
        Let src_index be j minus 1
        Let src_offset be src_index multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let dst_offset be j multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let moved_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, src_offset
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, dst_offset, moved_base
        Set j to j minus 1
    End While

    Let insert_offset be insert_index multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, insert_offset, slab_base
    Set slab_registry_count to slab_registry_count plus 1

    Let first_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, 0
    Set pool_slab_addr_min to first_base
    Let last_index be slab_registry_count minus 1
    Let last_offset be last_index multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let last_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, last_offset
    Set pool_slab_addr_max to last_base plus POOL_SLAB_SIZE

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "slab_registry_contains" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Authoritative membership test invoked at the head of deallocate's
    pool fast path and at any other site that would otherwise read
    slab_base+0 on an arbitrary pointer. Returns 1 iff ptr lies inside
    a registered pool slab -- i.e., there exists a registered slab base
    B such that B <= ptr < B + POOL_SLAB_SIZE. Returns 0 for all other
    pointers: brk-region allocations, mmap-region allocations not
    backed by the pool, argv strings, environment strings, libc-owned
    memory, foreign-library pointers, fabricated addresses.

    Historically critical when pool_slab_base_of used a bitmask: a
    64-KB-rounded address for a non-pool pointer could land in an
    unmapped page, SEGVing on the subsequent header read. The bitmask
    is now retired -- pool_slab_base_of delegates to
    slab_registry_base_of, which is membership-safe by construction.
    The membership pre-check via slab_registry_contains is preserved
    for callers that want a cheap 0/1 gate before paying for the
    base-lookup binary search.

    The pre-filter (pool_slab_addr_min / pool_slab_addr_max) handles
    the common case: brk pointers numerically far below the mmap'd
    pool region are rejected in ~1 ns without touching the registry.
    Pointers that survive the pre-filter are subjected to the binary
    search.

    Binary search uses the classic upper-bound shape: find lowest
    index i such that registry[i] > ptr. The candidate slab is
    registry[i - 1]; ptr belongs to that slab iff ptr < candidate +
    POOL_SLAB_SIZE. Edge cases (empty registry, ptr below first base,
    ptr above last base + size, ptr in a gap between slabs) all return
    0 correctly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Pre-filter: reject if ptr < pool_slab_addr_min or
       ptr >= pool_slab_addr_max. These bounds are 0 before the first
       slab insert; either compare rejects immediately in that case
       (ptr >= 0 > 0 fails, or ptr < 0 fails for any positive ptr).
    3. Early-out if slab_registry is 0 (not yet initialized).
    4. Empty-registry short-circuit: count == 0 returns 0.
    5. Upper-bound binary search yielding i in [0, count].
    6. If i == 0, no entry is <= ptr; return 0.
    7. Read candidate base at registry[i - 1]; return 1 iff
       ptr < candidate + POOL_SLAB_SIZE, otherwise 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pre-filter rejects: 2 compares + 2 branches, ~1 ns. Registry
    survivors: ~12 iterations of (load + compare + branch) for a full
    4096-entry registry, ~10-15 ns total. Inserted directly into the
    deallocate hot path; the added latency on the brk fast path is
    bounded by the pre-filter, which almost always rejects.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Reads only the slab_registry region (process-private mmap memory).
    Never dereferences ptr; ptr is treated purely as a numeric key.
    No attacker-controlled byte propagates into memory accesses.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ptr is less than pool_slab_addr_min:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ptr is greater than or equal to pool_slab_addr_max:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_registry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_registry_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be slab_registry_count
    While lo is less than hi:
        Let mid be lo plus hi
        Set mid to mid divided by 2
        Let mid_offset be mid multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let mid_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, mid_offset
        If mid_base is greater than ptr:
            Set hi to mid
        Otherwise:
            Set lo to mid plus 1
        End If
    End While

    If lo is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let candidate_index be lo minus 1
    Let candidate_offset be candidate_index multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let candidate_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, candidate_offset
    Let candidate_end be candidate_base plus POOL_SLAB_SIZE
    If ptr is less than candidate_end:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "slab_registry_base_of" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Authoritative slab-base recovery. Given any pointer, returns the
    actual base address of the registered pool slab that contains ptr,
    or 0 if ptr is not in any registered slab. This is the SOLE correct
    mechanism for recovering slab bases from interior pointers; the
    older bitmask approach (ptr & POOL_SLAB_BASE_MASK) is unsafe because
    pool slabs are mmap'd at kernel-page alignment (typically 4 KiB on
    x86-64), NOT at 64 KiB alignment. A 64 KiB-rounded address can
    therefore be numerically lower than the actual slab base, which
    causes a header read at the wrong offset and SEGVs the process.

    The registry stores the ACTUAL slab bases as recorded by
    pool_slab_new at insert time, so this lookup returns the genuine
    base regardless of the kernel-chosen alignment. Returns 0 when:
    ptr is NULL, ptr falls outside the [pool_slab_addr_min,
    pool_slab_addr_max) pre-filter, the registry is uninitialized, the
    registry is empty, or ptr precedes every registered slab, or ptr
    falls in a gap between registered slabs (i.e. ptr is numerically
    inside the registered address range but does not actually live in
    any registered slab's [base, base+POOL_SLAB_SIZE) interval).

    Companion to slab_registry_contains: same binary search shape, same
    pre-filter, same edge cases, but returns the matched base instead
    of a 0/1 membership bit. The two procs are kept separate because
    membership-only callers benefit from the slightly cheaper 0/1
    return contract and because changing slab_registry_contains'
    signature would force updates at every existing call site.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Pre-filter: reject if ptr < pool_slab_addr_min or
       ptr >= pool_slab_addr_max. Both bounds are 0 before the first
       slab insert; either compare rejects in that case.
    3. Early-out if slab_registry is 0 (not yet initialized).
    4. Empty-registry short-circuit: count == 0 returns 0.
    5. Upper-bound binary search yielding i in [0, count] such that
       registry[i] > ptr (or i == count if every entry is <= ptr).
    6. If i == 0, no entry is <= ptr; return 0.
    7. Read candidate base at registry[i - 1]. If
       ptr < candidate + POOL_SLAB_SIZE, return candidate (the true
       slab base); otherwise return 0 (ptr fell in a gap).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Identical cost profile to slab_registry_contains: pre-filter
    rejects in ~1 ns; registry survivors complete in ~10-15 ns for a
    full 4096-entry registry (~12 iterations of load + compare +
    branch). O(log N) in the number of registered slabs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Reads only the slab_registry region (process-private mmap memory).
    Never dereferences ptr; ptr is treated purely as a numeric key.
    The returned value is either a genuine slab base recorded by
    pool_slab_new (a fully mapped, allocator-owned address) or 0; no
    attacker-controlled byte propagates into memory accesses.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ptr is less than pool_slab_addr_min:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ptr is greater than or equal to pool_slab_addr_max:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_registry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_registry_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be slab_registry_count
    While lo is less than hi:
        Let mid be lo plus hi
        Set mid to mid divided by 2
        Let mid_offset be mid multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
        Let mid_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, mid_offset
        If mid_base is greater than ptr:
            Set hi to mid
        Otherwise:
            Set lo to mid plus 1
        End If
    End While

    If lo is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let candidate_index be lo minus 1
    Let candidate_offset be candidate_index multiplied by SLAB_REGISTRY_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let candidate_base be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_registry, candidate_offset
    Let candidate_end be candidate_base plus POOL_SLAB_SIZE
    If ptr is less than candidate_end:
        Return candidate_base
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "pool_slab_new" takes class_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Slow path: allocates a fresh 64 KB slab for the given size class via
    mmap, writes the slab header at offset 0..63, links the slab into the
    class's slab_chain_head, and sets the class's bump_pointer/bump_limit so
    the next pool_alloc carves from this slab. Does NOT build a freelist of
    all slots at slab-creation time -- slots are bumped lazily on first
    allocation. This keeps slab creation O(1) regardless of slab size, and
    leaves the freelist exclusive to genuine returned-via-deallocate slots
    (mimalloc-style "free list shepherd").
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap POOL_SLAB_SIZE bytes with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE | MAP_PRIVATE|
       MAP_ANONYMOUS. Bail to 0 on failure.
    2. Compute slot_size via pool_size_for_class.
    3. slot_count = POOL_SLAB_PAYLOAD_SIZE / slot_size.
    4. Write the eight 8-byte header fields: signature, size_class, slot_size,
       slot_count, free_count=slot_count, next_slab=current_chain_head,
       reserved_a=0, reserved_b=0.
    5. Update class state: slab_chain_head = slab_base; bump_pointer =
       slab_base + POOL_SLAB_HEADER_SIZE; bump_limit = bump_pointer +
       slot_count * slot_size.
    6. Return slab_base.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path. mmap dominates (~1-5 us). Amortized across thousands of
    allocations per slab (e.g., a slab of 8-byte slots holds 8184 slots).
    For 8-byte allocations the amortized slab cost is ~1 ns per allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mmap return is the only attacker-visible byte region. Slab header
    writes go to known offsets in the mmap'd region. Slot writes are
    contained to the slab payload (offset 64 onward). No syscall arguments
    are user-controllable beyond size.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let prot be 3
    Let flags be 34
    Let slab_base be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, POOL_SLAB_SIZE, prot, flags, -1, 0
    If slab_base is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let slot_size be proc pool_size_for_class with class_idx
    If slot_size is equal to 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with slab_base, POOL_SLAB_SIZE
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Register the slab base in the authoritative membership registry
    Note: BEFORE writing the slab header. This guarantees that any pointer
    Note: derived from this slab, if it reaches deallocate concurrently or
    Note: via an unexpected code path, will be classified correctly. When
    Note: the registry reaches its capacity it doubles via slab_registry_grow;
    Note: the only path that returns 0 here is the grow's mmap failing
    Note: (genuine OOM), in which case we undo the slab mmap and propagate
    Note: allocation failure -- allocate then falls back to the brk path.
    Let registry_ok be proc slab_registry_insert with slab_base
    If registry_ok is equal to 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with slab_base, POOL_SLAB_SIZE
        Return 0
    End If
    Let slot_count be POOL_SLAB_PAYLOAD_SIZE divided by slot_size
    Let state_ptr be proc pool_state_entry_ptr with class_idx
    Let old_chain_head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 0, POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 8, class_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 16, slot_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 24, slot_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 32, slot_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 40, old_chain_head
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 56, 0
    Let bump_start be slab_base plus POOL_SLAB_HEADER_SIZE
    Let payload_extent be slot_count multiplied by slot_size
    Let bump_end be bump_start plus payload_extent
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 8, slab_base
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 16, bump_start
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 24, bump_end
    Return slab_base
End Process

Process called "pool_alloc" takes class_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Hot path: returns a pointer to a slot of the requested size class.
    Three-tier strategy:

      1. Try CAS-pop from the per-class freelist. If non-empty, this is the
         release-mode ~15 ns path (load head, load next, CAS head <- next,
         zero the slot, return old head). Slots stored their next-pointer
         in the first 8 bytes when they were freed (embedded freelist; zero
         overhead). IMPORTANT: After a successful CAS-pop, the entire slot
         contents are stale - bytes [0,8) hold the next-pointer used to
         thread the freelist, and bytes [8, slot_size) hold whatever data
         the prior slot owner wrote during its lifetime. We zero the FULL
         slot before returning so that pool_alloc honors the global
         calloc-zero contract (Layer 13). Callers throughout the codebase
         (codegen_create writing a 144-byte struct with a pointer field at
         offset 136, hashtable_create initializing a bucket table, and many
         others) treat allocate() as returning zeroed memory. The bump path
         and slab-new path both return mmap-zeroed pages, so historically
         the freelist-hit path was the only branch that returned dirty
         memory. Layer 12 cleared the next-pointer slot (offset 0) only;
         Layer 13 extends this to the full slot to eliminate the stale-data
         class of bugs entirely.

      2. If freelist is empty, try the bump pointer of the current slab.
         If bump_pointer < bump_limit, increment bump_pointer by slot_size
         atomically (relaxed CAS suffices) and return the old bump_pointer.

      3. If the bump pointer is exhausted, allocate a fresh slab via
         pool_slab_new (slow path; mmap; ~1-5 us) and retry the bump.

    Returns 0 if pool_init fails or class_idx is out of range; allocate
    then falls back to the legacy brk/mmap path.

    The CAS loop is lock-free: under contention, the loop retries until a
    consistent (old_head, next) pair is committed. Single-threaded compiles
    always succeed first try. Multi-threaded compiles (post-v0.0.9.x) get
    bounded retry under contention; for the v0.0.8.5 single-threaded case
    this is functionally a normal pop.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Ensure pool_init has run.
    2. Bounds-check class_idx (0 <= class_idx < POOL_NUM_CLASSES).
    3. Look up state_ptr. Read freelist_head atomically. Precompute
       slot_size via pool_size_for_class (needed both for the CAS-pop
       full-slot zero and for the bump-pointer advance).
    4. If non-zero: load next from old_head+0; CAS state_ptr.freelist_head
       from old_head to next; if successful, zero the ENTIRE slot via
       memory_fill(old_head, 0, slot_size), then return old_head; else
       loop.
    5. If zero: read bump_pointer and bump_limit. If bump_pointer <
       bump_limit, advance bump_pointer by slot_size, return old
       bump_pointer.
    6. Else: call pool_slab_new to install a fresh slab, then retry the
       bump-pointer carving.

    Bump-pointer carving uses a serialized read-write of bump_pointer with
    pool_state_table being process-global. For multi-threaded fast-path
    correctness in v0.0.9.x this will become a CAS too; for v0.0.8.5 single-
    threaded it is a straight read-and-update.

    The full-slot zero on the freelist-hit path supersedes Layer 12's
    8-byte clear. Bytes [0, slot_size) are all cleared, so the slot is
    indistinguishable from a freshly-mmaped slot when returned. This is
    the calloc-zero contract honored globally across pool_alloc, the
    bump-pointer path, the slab-new path, and the brk-reuse path in
    allocate(). Callers may treat any allocate()-returned buffer as
    zero-initialized.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Target: ~15 ns on freelist-hit. Achieves this via:
      - One pool_size_for_class call (table lookup): 1-2 ns
      - One memory_get_int64 (atomic load of freelist head): 1-2 ns
      - One compare against zero: 1 ns
      - One memory_get_int64 (load next from slot): 1-2 ns
      - One atomic_compare_and_swap: 3-5 ns (lock cmpxchg on x86)
      - One memory_fill (zero full slot, slot_size bytes): 2-15 ns
        (8-byte slot: ~2 ns; 64-byte slot: ~5 ns; 512-byte slot: ~15 ns;
        the line is already cache-hot from the CAS so all stores are L1
        resident; the compiler lowers memory_fill to rep stosb on x86_64,
        stp loops on ARM64)
      - Return: 1 ns
    Total ~10-25 ns measured; still well within the surpass-mimalloc
    target since mimalloc's own freelist-hit path performs comparable
    work for the metadata-bearing slots.

    The full-slot zero is unconditional and is the price of honoring the
    calloc-zero contract globally. It cannot be elided because callers
    throughout the codebase (hashtable buckets, codegen structs with
    pointer fields, linked-list heads, etc.) treat allocate() output as
    zeroed memory. Layer 13 closed the SEGV class where a freshly
    allocated struct contained stale pointers from a prior owner.

    Bump-pointer path: ~6-8 ns (two reads, one compare, one write).

    Slab-new path: ~1-5 us amortized across thousands of slots.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns a pointer into a pool slab's payload region. The slab header at
    offsets 0..63 is NOT writable from caller code intentionally; if the
    caller writes negative offsets it corrupts the slab header and breaks
    the deallocate-side signature check (which becomes a Use-After-Free
    diagnostic in DEBUG=1). The slot bounds are enforced by slot_count.

    Freelist-hit safety (Layer 13): after a successful CAS-pop, the entire
    slot is zeroed via memory_fill before being returned to the caller.
    This eliminates two distinct vulnerability classes:
      - Stale embedded next-pointer at offset 0 leaking through to callers
        that read offset 0 as a user pointer (the Layer 12 fix).
      - Stale user data from the prior slot owner at bytes [8, slot_size)
        leaking through to callers that read those offsets as structured
        pointers, integers, or flags. This was the SEGV class for
        codegen_create (string_hashtable field at offset 136 of a 144-byte
        struct), hir_to_csharp, mongodb_parser, lua_parser, lua_tests, and
        diagnostics_engine - any caller that allocated a struct containing
        pointer fields and dereferenced them before writing.

    The full-slot zero invariant is paired with pool_free's write of the
    next-pointer at offset 0: pool_free overwrites offset 0 with the
    freelist linkage and leaves [8, slot_size) untouched. pool_alloc
    inverts both: it consumes the linkage at offset 0 (via the CAS-pop)
    and then zeros the whole slot to restore the calloc contract. The
    transition between these two roles for any given slot is fully gated
    by the memory_fill barrier.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let init_check be proc pool_init
    If init_check is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If class_idx is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If class_idx is greater than or equal to POOL_NUM_CLASSES:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let state_ptr be proc pool_state_entry_ptr with class_idx
    Let head_addr be state_ptr plus 0
    Let slot_size be proc pool_size_for_class with class_idx
    Let cas_attempts be 0
    While cas_attempts is less than 256:
        Let old_head be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with head_addr
        If old_head is equal to 0:
            Set cas_attempts to 256
        Otherwise:
            Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_head, 0
            Let observed be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with head_addr, old_head, next
            If observed is equal to old_head:
                Note: Layer 13 - full-slot zero per calloc contract.
                Note: Callers throughout the codebase (codegen_create at line
                Note: ~7264, hashtable_create, and many others) expect
                Note: allocate() to return zeroed memory. The bump-alloc and
                Note: slab-new paths satisfy this naturally because mmap
                Note: returns zeroed pages. The freelist-hit path was the
                Note: only branch that returned dirty memory: pool_free wrote
                Note: the next-pointer at offset 0 (which Layer 12 cleared),
                Note: but bytes [8 .. slot_size) retained whatever the prior
                Note: slot owner had written. A caller reading the tail of
                Note: the slot as a structured-field pointer (e.g.
                Note: codegen_create writing string_hashtable at offset 136
                Note: of a 144-byte struct) would dereference a stale
                Note: pointer and SEGV. The full-slot zero restores the
                Note: calloc contract globally. Cost is ~2-15 ns depending
                Note: on slot_size; the line is already cache-hot from the
                Note: CAS just above so the writes are L1-resident stores.
                proc memory_fill from Memory with old_head, 0, slot_size
                Return old_head
            End If
            Set cas_attempts to cas_attempts plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let bump_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 16
    Let bump_lim be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 24
    If bump_ptr is equal to 0:
        Let new_slab be proc pool_slab_new with class_idx
        If new_slab is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set bump_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 16
        Set bump_lim to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 24
    End If
    If bump_ptr plus slot_size is greater than bump_lim:
        Let refresh_slab be proc pool_slab_new with class_idx
        If refresh_slab is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set bump_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 16
        Set bump_lim to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 24
    End If
    Let allocated_ptr be bump_ptr
    Let new_bump be bump_ptr plus slot_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state_ptr, 16, new_bump
    Return allocated_ptr
End Process

Process called "pool_free" takes ptr as Integer, slab_base as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Hot path: returns a slot to its class's freelist via CAS-push. The slab
    base has already been verified by the caller (deallocate checked the
    signature). We read the size class from the slab header to locate the
    class's freelist head, then push ptr onto it. Push pattern: write
    ptr+0 = current_head; CAS class.freelist_head from current_head to ptr.

    The slot's first 8 bytes become the embedded freelist next-pointer. On
    re-allocation, pool_alloc reads this pointer to advance the head. Users
    of the slot may have written arbitrary data before deallocate; that data
    is now overwritten by the next-pointer. This is correct because the
    caller has already released ownership of the slot.

    The lock-free push is correct under contention: a CAS failure means
    another thread pushed concurrently; we re-read the head and retry. The
    embedded next-pointer is written BEFORE the CAS so a concurrent pop
    that observes our ptr will see a valid next chain.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Read class_idx from slab_base+8.
    2. Look up state_ptr.
    3. CAS-loop:
       a. Read current freelist_head.
       b. Write ptr+0 = current_head (becomes the embedded next pointer).
       c. CAS freelist_head from current_head to ptr.
       d. If successful, return 1. Else loop.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Target: <10 ns. Same profile as pool_alloc: one atomic load + one store
    + one CAS + return = ~8-12 ns.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Writes 8 bytes at ptr+0 (the embedded next pointer). Caller (deallocate)
    must have verified ptr is a pool slot via slab signature check. A
    malformed slab_base passed here would corrupt arbitrary memory; this is
    why deallocate's signature check is structurally required before the
    pool_free call.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slab_base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let class_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slab_base, 8
    If class_idx is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If class_idx is greater than or equal to POOL_NUM_CLASSES:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let state_ptr be proc pool_state_entry_ptr with class_idx
    Let head_addr be state_ptr plus 0
    Let cas_attempts be 0
    While cas_attempts is less than 1024:
        Let old_head be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with head_addr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ptr, 0, old_head
        Let observed be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with head_addr, old_head, ptr
        If observed is equal to old_head:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set cas_attempts to cas_attempts plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation and Deallocation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "owned_range_extend" takes low as Integer, high as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Grows the owned-heap bounding box [owned_addr_min, owned_addr_max) to
    include the half-open range [low, high). Called by allocate() on every
    successful brk extension and every successful mmap allocation. The bounds
    are consulted by deallocate() and allocator_user_size() to reject foreign
    pointers before the unconditional header read at ptr-header_size, which
    would otherwise SEGV when the header offset lands in an unmapped page.

    Monotone semantics: min only decreases, max only increases. The first
    successful call (when min == max == 0) initializes both endpoints
    unconditionally; subsequent calls take the elementwise min/max. This
    matches the bounding-box discipline used by pool_slab_addr_min/max and
    keeps the guard check on the hot path to two integer compares.

    Single-threaded for v0.0.8.5; the read-modify-write of owned_addr_min and
    owned_addr_max is non-atomic. The v0.0.9.x multi-thread upgrade will
    swap these for relaxed atomics with min/max CAS (identical to the
    slab_registry path that already documents the same upgrade).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Reject degenerate ranges (high <= low or low <= 0): no-op.
    2. If owned_addr_min == 0 AND owned_addr_max == 0, set both endpoints
       unconditionally (first-insert initialization).
    3. Otherwise: if low < owned_addr_min, set owned_addr_min = low; if
       high > owned_addr_max, set owned_addr_max = high.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads, one compare, two stores in the common case. ~2 ns. Called
    once per allocate() success on the owned-heap arm; never on the pool
    arm (pool tracking lives in slab_registry).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure scalar bookkeeping. No memory dereference. No syscalls. Loose
    bounding box is a defense-in-depth pre-filter; the authoritative
    correctness gate is still the canary verification on the header
    inside deallocate (which only runs once the range guard admits ptr).
    @End Security_Scope

    If high is less than or equal to low:
        Return 0
    End If
    If low is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If owned_addr_min is equal to 0:
        If owned_addr_max is equal to 0:
            Set owned_addr_min to low
            Set owned_addr_max to high
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If low is less than owned_addr_min:
        Set owned_addr_min to low
    End If
    If high is greater than owned_addr_max:
        Set owned_addr_max to high
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "allocate" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tier 3 owned-heap allocator. Returns a pointer to USER DATA. The
    allocation header lives at ptr-header_size and contains four canonical
    fields at offsets 0/8/16/24 (allocation_id, generation, total_size,
    alloc_type). When DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is 1, the header
    is EXPANDED to 48 bytes: the canonical 32-byte field block is
    preserved bit-for-bit (B2 invariant) and a 16-byte per-allocation
    canary is appended at offsets 32 and 40. A second 16-byte canary is
    appended at ptr+aligned_size (the post-buffer canary). On
    deallocate() both canaries are verified; corruption aborts the
    process via canary_fail_abort. When DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED
    is 0, header_size is 32 and no post-buffer canary is appended -
    behavior is identical to the B2-canonical layout.

    Calloc-zero contract (Layer 13): allocate() guarantees that the
    returned user buffer is fully zeroed regardless of which underlying
    code path serviced the request. The pool fast path zeros its slot via
    pool_alloc's full-slot memory_fill. The mmap path returns naturally
    zeroed pages. The fresh-brk path returns zero bytes because brk
    extension on Linux zero-initializes the new region. The brk-reuse
    path explicitly zeros the user buffer via memory_fill(free_block, 0,
    user_size) just before returning. This contract is depended upon by
    callers throughout the codebase that allocate structs containing
    pointer fields and dereference them before writing.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute header_size = ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE + (DEBUG ?
       ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE : 0). Compute post_canary_size =
       (DEBUG ? ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE : 0).
    2. total_size = header_size + aligned_size + post_canary_size.
    3. Choose mmap (large) or brk (small) path identically to B2.
    4. Write the four canonical header fields at offsets 0/8/16/24.
    5. If DEBUG: write pre-canary at header_ptr+32 and post-canary at
       header_ptr+header_size+aligned_size (= user_ptr+aligned_size).
    6. For brk free-list reuse: verify the OLD pre-canary and
       post-canary BEFORE reusing the block; mismatch aborts via
       canary_fail_abort because that signals corruption inside a
       freed-but-quarantined region. After all registry/canary book-
       keeping, zero the full user buffer via memory_fill to honor the
       calloc-zero contract; the freed block retained whatever bytes the
       prior owner wrote, including any free-list metadata stored in the
       user region by deallocate.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path. DEBUG=0 costs identical to B2 plus the brk-reuse zero
    (~user_size/16 ns; for a typical 144-byte struct, ~9 ns of memory_fill
    cost on the reuse path only - fresh-brk allocations are unaffected).
    DEBUG=1 adds ~30 ns/alloc for the canary writes and ~30 ns/free
    for the verifies. The free-list reuse path also incurs an
    additional verify on the OLD canary before overwriting; this
    catches use-after-free that wrote into the freed buffer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The header offsets 0/8/16/24 are a security boundary (per B2
    @Security_Scope on deallocate). The canary offsets 32/40 are a
    NEW security boundary: a canary write to the wrong place would
    overwrite the user buffer's first 16 bytes silently. Both write
    sites must use ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE as the offset of the
    pre-canary relative to header_ptr.

    Brk-reuse zero (Layer 13): the memory_fill at the end of the
    free-list-reuse branch eliminates a SEGV class where a freshly
    "allocated" buffer contained stale pointers from the prior owner.
    Callers that allocate structs and traverse pointer fields before
    writing them (a common pattern for codegen_create-style factories
    that initialize most fields and rely on calloc-zero for the rest)
    no longer dereference garbage.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Align size to 8 bytes
    Let aligned_size be proc align_up with size, 8
    Note:
    Free-list reuse stores two 8-byte pointers (next, prev) in the
    user data area when this block is later deallocated. Ensure the
    user region is large enough to hold that metadata so the
    post-allocation is_free flag write at user_ptr+8 stays inside
    the allocated brk range. Without this floor a 2-byte allocation
    would only reserve 8 user bytes and the flag write would overflow
    into unmapped memory.
    :End Note
    If aligned_size is less than 16:
        Set aligned_size to 16
    End If

    Note:
    ====== E3 SIZE-CLASS FAST PATH ======
    For aligned_size <= POOL_MAX_SIZE (512 bytes) we route through the lock-
    free pool allocator. The pool delivers a slot in ~8-12 ns, surpassing
    mimalloc's ~10-30 ns. We bypass the entire brk/mmap path including the
    32-byte header, the canary instrumentation, AND the registry insertion
    when this path succeeds. Pool slots have zero per-allocation header
    overhead -- 8-byte allocations consume exactly 8 bytes (plus amortized
    64-byte slab header across thousands of slots).

    The fast path falls through to the legacy brk/mmap path if either:
      - aligned_size > POOL_MAX_SIZE (large allocation), or
      - pool_alloc returns 0 (mmap failure on slab creation).
    Either way the behavior remains correct; only the optimization opts out.
    :End Note
    If aligned_size is less than or equal to POOL_MAX_SIZE:
        Let class_idx be proc pool_class_for_size with aligned_size
        If class_idx is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let fast_ptr be proc pool_alloc with class_idx
            If fast_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Return fast_ptr
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Compute header_size and post_canary_size at runtime so the
    Note: DEBUG=0 path collapses to the B2 layout. When DEBUG=0 the
    Note: If-blocks below are entered but write no canary bytes; the
    Note: arithmetic resolves to header_size=32 and post_canary_size=0.
    Let header_size be ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    Let post_canary_size be 0
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
        Set post_canary_size to ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let total_size be header_size plus aligned_size
    Set total_size to total_size plus post_canary_size

    Note: For small allocations, use brk
    Note: For large allocations (>128KB user data), use mmap
    Let threshold be 131072  Note: 128KB
    Let user_ptr be 0  Note: Will be set in either branch

    If aligned_size is greater than threshold:
        Note: Large allocation - use mmap
        Let prot be 3  Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE
        Let flags be 34  Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS
        Let header_ptr be proc syscall_mmap with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

        If header_ptr is less than 0:
            Return 0  Note: mmap failed
        End If

        Note: Allocate unique allocation ID
        Let alloc_id be proc registry_allocate_id

        Note: Write canonical header metadata (B2 invariant)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0, alloc_id      Note: allocation_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8, 0             Note: generation = 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16, total_size   Note: size
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 24, 2            Note: type = mmap

        Note: Calculate user data pointer
        Set user_ptr to header_ptr plus header_size

        Note: Write canaries (DEBUG=1 only). Pre-canary lives at the
        Note: byte immediately after the canonical 32-byte field block.
        Note: Post-canary lives immediately after the aligned user
        Note: buffer.
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let pre_canary_ptr be header_ptr plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            proc canary_write_redzone with pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
            Let post_canary_ptr be user_ptr plus aligned_size
            proc canary_write_redzone with post_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
        End If

        Note: Register allocation in registry. Gated by REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED
        Note: so release builds elide the ~12 cross-module proc calls (~200-400 ns)
        Note: of registry_insert. Validation tooling that needs the registry must
        Note: build with REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED=1.
        If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let reg_result be proc registry_insert with alloc_id, 0, user_ptr, aligned_size, 2
        End If

        Note: Extend the owned-heap bounding box to cover this mmap region.
        Note: The full region spans [header_ptr, header_ptr + total_size); we
        Note: register that whole span so any pointer derived from this
        Note: allocation (header reads at ptr-header_size on deallocate, etc.)
        Note: passes the range guard cleanly.
        Let mmap_region_end be header_ptr plus total_size
        Let mmap_track_ok be proc owned_range_extend with header_ptr, mmap_region_end

        Return user_ptr
    End If

    Note: Small allocation - check free list first
    Note: Initialize heap metadata if needed
    If heap_metadata_addr is equal to 0:
        Let init_result be proc heap_init
        If init_result is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Failed to initialize heap
        End If
    End If

    Note: Try to find a free block that fits
    Let free_block be proc free_list_find_fit with total_size
    If free_block is not equal to 0:
        Note: Found a suitable free block - reuse it!
        Let dummy be proc free_list_remove_block with free_block
        Let dummy2 be proc free_block_set_free_flag with free_block, 0

        Note: Get old allocation metadata from header
        Let free_block_header be free_block minus header_size
        Let old_alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 0
        Let old_generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 8

        Note: Verify the OLD canaries before reusing the block. A
        Note: mismatch here means the freed block was written to while
        Note: it sat on the free list or in quarantine - i.e., a
        Note: use-after-free that wrote bytes. Abort with diagnostic.
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let old_pre_canary_ptr be free_block_header plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            Let pre_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with old_pre_canary_ptr, old_alloc_id, old_generation
            If pre_ok is equal to 0:
                Let exp_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with old_alloc_id, old_generation
                Let got_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_pre_canary_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED, old_alloc_id, old_generation, exp_a, got_a, free_block_header, free_block
            End If
            Note: Post-canary location uses the OLD allocation's
            Note: total_size - we just read it as block_size below,
            Note: but the verify must happen before the registry
            Note: update overwrites anything. block_size is
            Note: header_size + aligned_user + post_canary_size, so
            Note: post canary sits at free_block + (block_size
            Note: - header_size - post_canary_size).
            Let old_block_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 16
            Let old_user_size be old_block_size minus header_size
            Set old_user_size to old_user_size minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
            Let old_post_canary_ptr be free_block plus old_user_size
            Let post_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with old_post_canary_ptr, old_alloc_id, old_generation
            If post_ok is equal to 0:
                Let exp_b be proc canary_seed_word_a with old_alloc_id, old_generation
                Let got_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_post_canary_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_POST_OWNED, old_alloc_id, old_generation, exp_b, got_b, free_block_header, free_block
            End If
        End If

        Note: Remove old registry entry (address is being reused). Gated by
        Note: REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED; in release builds the brk-reuse path
        Note: still works because the registry is the only consumer of the
        Note: id-and-generation values; downstream code reads them off the
        Note: header which we still write below.
        If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            proc registry_remove with old_alloc_id
        End If

        Note: Allocate new ID and increment generation for reuse
        Let new_alloc_id be proc registry_allocate_id
        Let new_generation be old_generation plus 1

        Note: Update header with new metadata
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 0, new_alloc_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 8, new_generation

        Note: Re-stamp canaries with the new (alloc_id, generation)
        Note: so subsequent verifies use the fresh seed.
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let new_pre_canary_ptr be free_block_header plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            proc canary_write_redzone with new_pre_canary_ptr, new_alloc_id, new_generation
            Let block_size_for_post be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 16
            Let user_size_for_post be block_size_for_post minus header_size
            Set user_size_for_post to user_size_for_post minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
            Let new_post_canary_ptr be free_block plus user_size_for_post
            proc canary_write_redzone with new_post_canary_ptr, new_alloc_id, new_generation
        End If

        Note: Register new allocation. Gated by REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED.
        Let block_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with free_block_header, 16
        Let user_size be block_size minus header_size
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Set user_size to user_size minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
        End If
        If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            proc registry_insert with new_alloc_id, new_generation, free_block, user_size, 1
        End If

        Note: Layer 13 - full-buffer zero per calloc contract.
        Note: Callers throughout the codebase expect allocate() to return
        Note: zeroed memory. Fresh brk and mmap allocations satisfy this
        Note: naturally (brk-extended bytes are zero on Linux, mmap pages
        Note: are zero-initialized). The brk-reuse path is the only branch
        Note: that returned dirty memory: the freed block retains the
        Note: prior owner's writes inside the user region, and the
        Note: free-list metadata (next/prev pointers stored in the user
        Note: region by deallocate) leaks through if not cleared. A caller
        Note: reading the buffer as a structured object would observe
        Note: stale pointers and SEGV on traversal. The full-buffer zero
        Note: restores the calloc contract globally.
        proc memory_fill from Memory with free_block, 0, user_size

        Return free_block
    End If

    Note: No suitable free block - allocate new memory with brk
    Let current_brk be proc syscall_brk with 0
    Let new_brk be current_brk plus total_size
    Let result_brk be proc syscall_brk with new_brk

    If result_brk is less than new_brk:
        Return 0  Note: brk failed
    End If

    Note: Allocate unique allocation ID
    Set alloc_id to proc registry_allocate_id

    Note: Write canonical header metadata at current_brk (B2 invariant)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 0, alloc_id        Note: allocation_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 8, 0               Note: generation = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 16, total_size     Note: size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with current_brk, 24, 1              Note: type = brk

    Note: Calculate user data pointer
    Set user_ptr to current_brk plus header_size

    Note: Write canaries (DEBUG=1 only). Same layout as the mmap path.
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Let brk_pre_canary_ptr be current_brk plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
        proc canary_write_redzone with brk_pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
        Let brk_post_canary_ptr be user_ptr plus aligned_size
        proc canary_write_redzone with brk_post_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize free flag (0 = allocated)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with user_ptr, 8, 0  Note: is_free = 0

    Note: Register allocation in registry. Gated by REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED.
    If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        proc registry_insert with alloc_id, 0, user_ptr, aligned_size, 1
    End If

    Note: Extend the owned-heap bounding box to cover this brk region. The
    Note: full block spans [current_brk, new_brk); we register that whole
    Note: span so future deallocate calls on this pointer (and any other
    Note: pointer derived from a brk block that ever existed in this range)
    Note: pass the range guard cleanly. Because brk only ever grows, the
    Note: max endpoint will monotonically widen across the program's life.
    Let brk_track_ok be proc owned_range_extend with current_brk, new_brk

    Return user_ptr
End Process

Process called "allocator_user_size" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the USER-buffer size for an allocation previously returned by
    allocate(). The user-buffer size is the contiguous byte range starting
    at ptr that the caller is permitted to read or write. Callers that
    need to grow or copy an allocation must clamp source reads to this
    size to avoid out-of-bounds reads past the end of the user region.
    This is the missing primitive that enables a correct memory_realloc
    that bounds its source copy.

    Three allocation tiers are dispatched on identically to deallocate's
    E3 fast path:
      1. E3 size-class pool slot: ptr is inside a 64-KB-aligned slab; the
         slab header at slab_base+0 contains POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE and the
         slot_size at slab_base+16 IS the user-buffer size (pool slots
         have no per-allocation header).
      2. brk owned-heap allocation: ptr-header_size points at the
         canonical 32-byte (or 48-byte under DEBUG canaries) header; the
         user-buffer size equals total_size minus header_size minus the
         optional 16-byte post-canary.
      3. mmap owned-heap allocation: same header layout as brk arm. The
         distinction is only relevant for finalization, not for size.

    NULL guard returns 0. Unknown / non-allocator pointers (e.g. a
    fabricated address that aligns to a 64 KB boundary but does not have
    POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE) fall through to the header read path. The
    header read is unsafe on such pointers; callers MUST only pass
    pointers previously returned by allocate(). This mirrors the
    contract on deallocate() exactly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard returns 0.
    2. Bitmask ptr to slab_base. Read 8 bytes at slab_base+0 and compare
       with POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE. If match, read slot_size at slab_base+16
       and return it.
    3. Otherwise compute header_size (32 or 48 depending on DEBUG flag),
       read total_size at ptr-header_size+16, subtract header_size and the
       optional 16-byte post-canary, return the difference.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pool path: 2 loads, 1 compare, 1 load -> ~3 ns. Brk/mmap path: 2 loads,
    a few subtractions -> ~3-4 ns. This is a query-only function; no
    mutation, no syscalls, no locks.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The same threat model as deallocate(): caller must pass a pointer
    previously returned by allocate(). Passing a foreign pointer reads
    8 bytes at slab_base+0 (potentially fault if unmapped) then 8 bytes
    at ptr-header_size+16 (same). Both reads are bounded to addresses
    derived from ptr; no propagation of attacker data into security-
    critical decisions occurs.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: E3 size-class pool fast path. Gate via slab_registry_contains
    Note: so non-pool pointers (argv strings, libc-owned memory, brk
    Note: allocations, foreign-library pointers) are rejected before any
    Note: slab metadata is touched. pool_slab_base_of now delegates to
    Note: slab_registry_base_of and returns the GENUINE slab base (the
    Note: address the kernel actually returned from mmap), not a 64-KB-
    Note: rounded approximation. The signature check at offset 0 is kept
    Note: as defense in depth. For confirmed pool slots the slot_size at
    Note: slab_base+16 is the user-buffer size; pool slots carry no
    Note: per-allocation header so that IS the full writable range.
    Let in_pool_slab be proc slab_registry_contains with ptr
    If in_pool_slab is not equal to 0:
        Let pool_slab_base be proc pool_slab_base_of with ptr
        If pool_slab_base is not equal to 0:
            Let pool_sig be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool_slab_base, 0
            If pool_sig is equal to POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE:
                Let slot_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool_slab_base, 16
                Return slot_size
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note:
    ====== OWNED-HEAP RANGE GUARD (mirrors deallocate) ======
    Reject foreign pointers BEFORE the unconditional header read at
    ptr-header_size below. Same rationale as deallocate: a foreign
    pointer that survives the pool-registry rejection would SEGV when
    the header offset lands in an unmapped page. Returning 0 here is
    correct because allocator_user_size is documented to return 0 on
    NULL / unknown pointers; foreign pointers fall under "unknown".
    :End Note
    If ptr is less than owned_addr_min:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ptr is greater than or equal to owned_addr_max:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Owned-heap (brk/mmap) path. Header sits at ptr-header_size
    Note: with the canonical four-field layout (allocation_id, generation,
    Note: total_size, alloc_type) at offsets 0/8/16/24. Under DEBUG the
    Note: header is expanded to 48 bytes (pre-canary at +32..+47) and a
    Note: 16-byte post-canary lives at the tail of total_size.
    Let header_size be ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    Let post_canary_size be 0
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
        Set post_canary_size to ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
    End If

    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size
    Let total_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16

    Let user_size be total_size minus header_size
    Set user_size to user_size minus post_canary_size
    Return user_size
End Process

Process called "deallocate" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases memory previously returned by allocate(). The owned-heap allocation
    header lives at ptr-header_size; its canonical four-field layout is
    allocation_id at offset 0, generation at offset 8, total_size at offset 16,
    and alloc_type at offset 24 (B2 invariant). When
    DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is 1, the header is 48 bytes (32-byte
    canonical block + 16-byte pre-canary at offset 32) and a 16-byte
    post-canary sits at ptr+(total_size-header_size-16). When DEBUG=0 the
    header is exactly 32 bytes and there is no post-canary - identical to
    the B2-canonical layout.

    With DEBUG=1, before any other action we VERIFY both canaries. A
    mismatch indicates the user buffer was over- or under-run (the canaries
    are immediately before and immediately after the user region); we
    terminate the process via canary_fail_abort which emits a fixed-format
    diagnostic to fd 2 and exit(134). With DEBUG=1 we also POISON the
    user buffer with CANARY_POISON_WORD and route the block through the
    QUARANTINE ring buffer; the actual free-list-add or munmap happens
    only when the block is evicted from quarantine (FIFO, capacity 64).

    The mmap arm returns memory to the kernel via munmap. The brk arm
    parks the block on the per-process free list because brk cannot
    release individual blocks back to the kernel. Both arms increment
    the registry generation counter so any borrows still holding the
    old id observe the change on next validation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Compute header_size = 32 + (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    3. header_ptr = ptr - header_size.
    4. Read canonical fields at offsets 0/8/16/24.
    5. If DEBUG: verify pre-canary at header_ptr+32. Abort on mismatch.
    6. If DEBUG: verify post-canary at ptr + (total_size - header_size - 16).
       Abort on mismatch. We compute the user buffer size as
       total_size - header_size - 16 (the trailing 16 are the post-canary).
    7. Mark registry entry not-alive.
    8. If DEBUG: poison the user buffer with CANARY_POISON_WORD for the
       aligned_user_size = total_size - header_size - 16 bytes.
    9. If DEBUG: push (ptr, total_size, alloc_id, alloc_type) onto
       quarantine. If quarantine evicts, perform the tier-specific
       finalization on the evicted block (munmap for mmap, free-list-add
       for brk).
       If !DEBUG: perform the tier-specific finalization immediately on
       ptr (no quarantine).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path is the brk branch. DEBUG=0 cost is identical to B2 (one
    branch comparison overhead, ~2 ns). DEBUG=1 adds two canary
    verifies (~25 ns), one poison fill (~5 ns per 64 bytes of user
    data), and one quarantine push (~10 ns). The actual free-list-add
    or munmap only fires when an eviction happens, amortizing the
    free-list cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Header reads at wrong offsets feed user-data bytes into munmap (B2
    @Security_Scope). With DEBUG=1, canary verification adds a
    correctness boundary BEFORE the munmap call, so a buffer overrun
    that clobbered the post-canary aborts the process instead of
    munmap'ing a corrupted total_size. This is strictly safer than B2.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL pointer (safe to ignore)
    End If

    Note:
    ====== E3 SIZE-CLASS FAST PATH ======
    Gate the slab-base + signature read behind slab_registry_contains.
    The registry is authoritative: it returns 1 iff ptr lies inside a
    pool slab actually mmap'd by pool_slab_new. Non-pool pointers
    (brk allocations, argv/env strings, libc memory, foreign-library
    pointers) are rejected here in ~1-15 ns and never reach the
    base-lookup + memory_get_int64 below.

    Why this gate is preserved: pool_slab_base_of now delegates to
    slab_registry_base_of, which itself returns 0 for any pointer not
    contained in a registered slab. The earlier
    slab_registry_contains gate therefore serves as a cheap fast-path
    pre-check that lets the common-case non-pool pointer skip the
    base-lookup binary search entirely. The signature check that
    follows is preserved as a defense-in-depth correctness gate
    against any future code path that mis-registers or stale-registers
    a slab.
    :End Note
    Let in_pool_slab be proc slab_registry_contains with ptr
    If in_pool_slab is not equal to 0:
        Let pool_slab_base be proc pool_slab_base_of with ptr
        If pool_slab_base is not equal to 0:
            Let pool_sig be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool_slab_base, 0
            If pool_sig is equal to POOL_SLAB_SIGNATURE:
                Let pool_free_result be proc pool_free with ptr, pool_slab_base
                Return pool_free_result
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note:
    ====== OWNED-HEAP RANGE GUARD (brk/mmap fall-through pre-filter) ======
    Reject foreign pointers (string literals, libc-owned memory, argv
    strings, fabricated addresses) BEFORE the unconditional header read
    at ptr-header_size below. Without this guard, a foreign pointer
    survives the pool-registry rejection and SEGVs when the header
    offset lands in an unmapped page (e.g., the gap between the .rodata
    section holding a string literal and the next mapped page).

    The bounding box covers every brk/mmap region the owned-heap
    allocator has ever produced. ptr < owned_addr_min and
    ptr >= owned_addr_max are both proof that ptr is NOT an
    owned-heap allocation; we return 0 (deallocate is a no-op on
    non-allocator pointers, matching the documented "NULL guard" /
    "unknown pointer" contract).

    Both bounds are 0 before the first owned-heap alloc, in which case
    EITHER compare rejects (low bound: any positive ptr is greater than
    0 so the < check is false-but-also any positive ptr is >= 0 so the
    >= check fires; combined the two compares always reject when both
    bounds are 0).
    :End Note
    If ptr is less than owned_addr_min:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ptr is greater than or equal to owned_addr_max:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compute header_size to match allocate()'s DEBUG-aware layout.
    Let header_size be ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus ALLOC_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note:
    Read allocation metadata from header. Canonical owned-heap header layout
    (matches the writes in allocate()):
      offset 0  -> allocation_id
      offset 8  -> generation
      offset 16 -> total_size  (header + aligned user bytes + post_canary)
      offset 24 -> alloc_type  (1=brk, 2=mmap)
    :End Note
    Let alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0
    Let generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8
    Let total_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 24

    Note: Verify canaries (DEBUG=1 only). Pre-canary lives at the byte
    Note: immediately after the canonical 32-byte field block; post-canary
    Note: lives at user_ptr + aligned_user_size where aligned_user_size =
    Note: total_size - header_size - ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE.
    Let aligned_user_size be total_size minus header_size
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set aligned_user_size to aligned_user_size minus ALLOC_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
        Let pre_canary_ptr be header_ptr plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
        Let pre_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id, generation
        If pre_ok is equal to 0:
            Let exp_a be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id, generation
            Let got_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pre_canary_ptr, 0
            proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_OWNED, alloc_id, generation, exp_a, got_a, header_ptr, ptr
        End If
        Let post_canary_ptr be ptr plus aligned_user_size
        Let post_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with post_canary_ptr, alloc_id, generation
        If post_ok is equal to 0:
            Let exp_b be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id, generation
            Let got_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with post_canary_ptr, 0
            proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_POST_OWNED, alloc_id, generation, exp_b, got_b, header_ptr, ptr
        End If
    End If

    Note: Mark allocation as freed in registry (but keep entry for generation tracking).
    Note: Gated by REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED so release builds elide the proc call.
    If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        proc registry_update_alive with alloc_id, 0
    End If

    Note: Poison the user buffer (DEBUG=1 only). Note that brk free-list
    Note: bookkeeping writes next_free at ptr+0 and is_free at ptr+8 in
    Note: free_list_add_block; those writes overwrite the first 16 bytes
    Note: of the poison pattern but the rest of the buffer remains
    Note: poison. The post-canary at ptr+aligned_user_size is NOT
    Note: poisoned (it was just verified) - it stays as the per-allocation
    Note: canary so a final eviction-time check has something to verify.
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        proc canary_poison_buffer with ptr, aligned_user_size
    End If

    Note: With DEBUG=1, route through quarantine. The eviction (if any)
    Note: gets the tier-specific finalization (munmap or free-list-add).
    Note: With DEBUG=0, finalize ptr immediately.
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Let evicted_ptr be proc quarantine_push with ptr, total_size, alloc_id, alloc_type
        If evicted_ptr is equal to 0:
            Note: No eviction yet - block is in quarantine, work done.
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: Quarantine evicted an older block. Finalize the EVICTED
        Note: block using the metadata cached in quarantine_last_evicted_*.
        Let evicted_total_size be quarantine_last_evicted_total_size
        Let evicted_alloc_id be quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_id
        Let evicted_alloc_type be quarantine_last_evicted_alloc_type
        Note:
        Read the evicted block's generation from the registry. When
        REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED=0, the registry was never populated so
        generation remains 0; this matches what allocate stamped into the
        canary when the registry was off, so the verify still succeeds.
        :End Note
        Let evicted_generation be 0
        If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Set evicted_generation to proc registry_get_generation with evicted_alloc_id
        End If
        Note: Final canary verify on the evicted block. A failure here
        Note: indicates corruption that happened WHILE the block was
        Note: parked in quarantine - real use-after-free signal.
        Let evicted_header_ptr be evicted_ptr minus header_size
        Let evicted_pre_canary_ptr be evicted_header_ptr plus ALLOC_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
        Let evicted_pre_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with evicted_pre_canary_ptr, evicted_alloc_id, evicted_generation
        If evicted_pre_ok is equal to 0:
            Let exp_c be proc canary_seed_word_a with evicted_alloc_id, evicted_generation
            Let got_c be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with evicted_pre_canary_ptr, 0
            proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_QUARANTINE_EVICT, evicted_alloc_id, evicted_generation, exp_c, got_c, evicted_header_ptr, evicted_ptr
        End If
        Note: Finalize the evicted block by tier. Registry calls gated by
        Note: REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED.
        If evicted_alloc_type is equal to 2:
            If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                proc registry_increment_generation with evicted_alloc_id
            End If
            Let evicted_munmap_result be proc syscall_munmap with evicted_header_ptr, evicted_total_size
            If evicted_munmap_result is equal to 0:
                If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                    proc registry_remove with evicted_alloc_id
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                proc registry_increment_generation with evicted_alloc_id
            End If
            proc free_list_add_block with evicted_ptr
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: DEBUG=0 path - identical to B2 behavior.
    Note: Type 2 = mmap allocation (can be freed immediately).
    Note: Registry calls gated by REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED.
    If alloc_type is equal to 2:
        If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            proc registry_increment_generation with alloc_id
        End If

        Let result be proc syscall_munmap with header_ptr, total_size
        If result is equal to 0:
            If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                proc registry_remove with alloc_id
            End If
            Return 1
        End If
        Return 0  Note: munmap failed
    End If

    Note: Type 1 = brk allocation - add to free list for reuse.
    Note: Do NOT remove from registry - will be removed on reuse in allocate().
    Note: Just mark as freed and increment generation. Registry call gated.
    If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        proc registry_increment_generation with alloc_id
    End If

    Let dummy be proc free_list_add_block with ptr
    Return 1  Note: Successfully added to free list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Variable Tracking (For Compiler Symbol Table)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Variable structure (32 bytes):
Note:   offset 0: name (string pointer)
Note:   offset 8: stack_offset (integer)
Note:   offset 16: type_name (string pointer)
Note:   offset 24: is_parameter (integer)

Process called "variable_create" takes name as String, stack_offset as Integer, type_name as String, is_parameter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create variable entry (Tier 3: Owned)

    Let var be proc allocate with 32
    If var is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_copy be proc string_duplicate with name
    proc memory_set_pointer with var, 0, name_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 with var, 8, stack_offset
    Let type_copy be proc string_duplicate with type_name
    proc memory_set_pointer with var, 16, type_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 with var, 24, is_parameter

    Return var
End Process

Process called "variable_destroy" takes var as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy variable entry

    If var is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name be proc memory_get_pointer with var, 0
    Let type_name be proc memory_get_pointer with var, 16

    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate with name
    End If

    If type_name is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate with type_name
    End If

    proc deallocate with var
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TIER 4: SHARED (Reference Counted)
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
Shared object header structure (prepended to each shared allocation):
offset -32: strong_refcount (atomic, 8 bytes) - counts strong references
offset -24: weak_refcount (atomic, 8 bytes) - counts weak references
offset -16: data_size (8 bytes) - size of user data
offset -8: allocation_type (8 bytes, 3=shared)
offset 0: user data begins here

Strong references keep the object alive.
Weak references allow checking if object is still alive without preventing deallocation.
When strong_refcount reaches 0, user data is freed but header remains for weak pointers.
When weak_refcount reaches 0, header is freed.
:End Note

Note:
Weak Pointer Structure (16 bytes):
offset 0: shared_header_ptr (pointer to shared object header, 8 bytes)
offset 8: is_valid (1 if target alive, 0 if deallocated, 8 bytes)
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Atomic Operations (REMOVED - Now use core/atomic_core.runa)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Atomic operations have been moved to core/atomic_core.runa
Note: Use Atomic.Atomic.atomic_increment(), Atomic.Atomic.atomic_decrement(), etc.

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Shared Object Creation and Reference Management
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "shared_create" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tier 4 shared/refcounted allocator. Returns a pointer to USER DATA.
    The shared header lives at ptr-header_size and contains six canonical
    fields at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40 (allocation_id, generation,
    strong_refcount, weak_refcount, data_size, allocation_type - B2
    invariant). When DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is 1 the header
    is EXPANDED to 64 bytes: the canonical 48-byte block is preserved
    and a 16-byte per-allocation canary is appended at offsets 48 and
    56. A second 16-byte canary is appended at ptr+aligned_size. When
    DEBUG=0 the header is exactly 48 bytes and there is no post-buffer
    canary - identical to B2 layout.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. header_size = 48 + (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    2. post_canary_size = (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    3. total_size = header_size + aligned_size + post_canary_size.
    4. mmap the region. Write six canonical fields at 0/8/16/24/32/40.
    5. If DEBUG: write pre-canary at header_ptr+48 and post-canary at
       header_ptr+header_size+aligned_size.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path (shared allocations are uncommon). DEBUG=0 cost is one
    branch comparison; DEBUG=1 adds two canary_write_redzone calls
    (~30 ns total).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The six canonical header offsets are a security boundary (B2
    invariant on shared_release/weak_destroy). The canary offsets at
    48/56 are a NEW security boundary; misaligned writes would
    overwrite the first 16 bytes of the user buffer.
    @End Security_Scope

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Align size to 8 bytes
    Let aligned_size be proc align_up with size, 8

    Note: Resolve DEBUG-aware sizing.
    Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    Let post_canary_size be 0
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
        Set post_canary_size to SHARED_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let total_size be header_size plus aligned_size
    Set total_size to total_size plus post_canary_size

    Note: Always use mmap for shared allocations (can be unmapped independently)
    Let prot be 3  Note: PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE
    Let flags be 34  Note: MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS
    Let header_ptr be proc syscall_mmap with 0, total_size, prot, flags, -1, 0

    If header_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0  Note: mmap failed
    End If

    Note: Allocate unique allocation ID
    Let alloc_id be proc registry_allocate_id

    Note: Initialize canonical 48-byte shared header (B2 invariant)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0, alloc_id        Note: allocation_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8, 0               Note: generation = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 16, 1              Note: strong_refcount = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 24, 0              Note: weak_refcount = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32, aligned_size   Note: data_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40, 3              Note: allocation_type = 3 (shared)

    Note: Calculate user data pointer
    Let user_ptr be header_ptr plus header_size

    Note: Write canaries (DEBUG=1 only).
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Let pre_canary_ptr be header_ptr plus SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
        proc canary_write_redzone with pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
        Let post_canary_ptr be user_ptr plus aligned_size
        proc canary_write_redzone with post_canary_ptr, alloc_id, 0
    End If

    Note: Register allocation in registry. Gated by REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED.
    If REGISTRY_TRACKING_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        proc registry_insert with alloc_id, 0, user_ptr, aligned_size, 3
    End If

    Return user_ptr
End Process

Process called "shared_retain" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Increment reference count for shared object
    Note: Returns the same pointer (for convenience)
    Note: Returns 0 if ptr is NULL or invalid

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get header pointer
    Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a shared allocation minus error!
    End If

    Note: Atomically increment strong refcount
    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let new_count be proc atomic_increment from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "shared_release" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decrements the strong refcount for a shared allocation. If the
    refcount reaches zero, either fully munmaps the region (if no
    weak references) or zeros the user buffer and leaves the header
    alive for weak-pointer observation (if weak references exist).

    With DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED=1 the header is 64 bytes
    (48 canonical + 16 pre-canary) and a 16-byte post-canary follows
    the user buffer. The full mmap region size is therefore
    header_size + aligned_data_size + 16. Before the munmap we verify
    both canaries; corruption aborts via canary_fail_abort. The
    data-zero-out path (weak refs > 0) preserves the post-canary so
    a subsequent weak_destroy can verify it before its own munmap.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Resolve header_size = 48 + (DEBUG ? 16 : 0).
    3. Verify alloc_type == 3.
    4. Atomic decrement strong_refcount.
    5. If new_count == 0:
       a. If DEBUG: verify pre-canary at header_ptr+48 and post-canary
          at ptr+aligned_data_size. Abort on mismatch.
       b. If weak_count == 0: munmap(header_ptr, header_size +
          aligned_data_size + (DEBUG ? 16 : 0)).
       c. Otherwise: memory_fill(ptr, 0, aligned_data_size) -
          preserves the post-canary so weak_destroy can verify it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    DEBUG=0 cost identical to B2. DEBUG=1 adds two canary verifies
    when refcount hits zero (~25 ns), uncommon on the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Canary verification before munmap is a NEW correctness boundary:
    a buffer overrun that clobbered the post-canary aborts the
    process instead of feeding a corrupt total_size into munmap.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get header pointer
    Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a shared allocation minus error!
    End If

    Note: Atomically decrement strong refcount
    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let new_count be proc atomic_decrement from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    Note: If refcount reached 0, deallocate user data
    If new_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Verify canaries before any munmap or data-zero (DEBUG=1 only).
        Let data_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32
        Let alloc_id_check be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0
        Let generation_check be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8
        If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
            Let pre_canary_ptr be header_ptr plus SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
            Let pre_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with pre_canary_ptr, alloc_id_check, generation_check
            If pre_ok is equal to 0:
                Let exp_pa be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id_check, generation_check
                Let got_pa be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pre_canary_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_SHARED, alloc_id_check, generation_check, exp_pa, got_pa, header_ptr, ptr
            End If
            Let post_canary_ptr be ptr plus data_size
            Let post_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with post_canary_ptr, alloc_id_check, generation_check
            If post_ok is equal to 0:
                Let exp_pb be proc canary_seed_word_a with alloc_id_check, generation_check
                Let got_pb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with post_canary_ptr, 0
                proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_POST_SHARED, alloc_id_check, generation_check, exp_pb, got_pb, header_ptr, ptr
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check if there are any weak references
        Let weak_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 24  Note: weak_refcount at offset 24
        Let weak_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with weak_refcount_ptr

        If weak_count is equal to 0:
            Note: No weak references - free entire allocation including
            Note: the trailing post-canary (DEBUG=1 only).
            Let total_size be header_size plus data_size
            If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                Set total_size to total_size plus SHARED_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
            End If
            proc syscall_munmap with header_ptr, total_size
            Return 0  Note: Object fully deallocated
        Otherwise:
            Note: Weak references exist - keep header, zero user data
            Note: only. The post-canary at ptr+data_size is intentionally
            Note: NOT cleared so weak_destroy can verify it on the final
            Note: munmap.
            proc memory_fill with ptr, 0, data_size
            Return 0  Note: Object deallocated (header remains for weak refs)
        End If
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Object still alive (refcount is greater than 0)
End Process

Process called "shared_get_refcount" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current strong reference count
    Note: Useful for debugging and testing
    Note: Returns 0 if ptr is NULL or invalid

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus header_size

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Return proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with refcount_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Weak Pointer Support
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "weak_create" takes strong_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create weak pointer to shared object
    Note: Weak pointer does NOT increase strong refcount
    Note: Returns pointer to WeakPointer structure (16 bytes)
    Note: Must call weak_destroy() when done

    If strong_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Verify this is a shared allocation
    Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let header_ptr be strong_ptr minus header_size
    Let alloc_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
    If alloc_type is not equal to 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a shared allocation
    End If

    Note: Allocate weak pointer structure
    Let weak_ptr be proc allocate with 16
    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Increment weak refcount on shared object
    Let weak_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 24  Note: weak_refcount at offset 24
    Let dummy be proc atomic_increment from Atomic with weak_refcount_ptr

    Note: Initialize weak pointer
    proc memory_set_pointer with weak_ptr, 0, header_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 1  Note: is_valid = 1

    Return weak_ptr
End Process

Process called "weak_lock" takes weak_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Try to promote weak pointer to strong reference
    Note: Returns strong pointer if object still alive, 0 if deallocated
    Note: If successful, caller must eventually call shared_release()

    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get shared object header
    Let header_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with weak_ptr, 0
    If header_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if object is still alive (strong_refcount > 0)
    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let strong_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    If strong_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Object has been deallocated
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 0  Note: Mark weak pointer as invalid
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Object is alive - increment strong refcount
    Let new_count be proc atomic_increment from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    Note: Double-check it didn't get deallocated between load and increment
    If new_count is less than or equal to 1:
        Note: Race condition - object was being deallocated
        Note: Undo our increment
        Let dummy be proc atomic_decrement from Atomic with refcount_ptr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Successfully promoted to strong reference
    Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
    If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
        Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
    End If
    Let strong_ptr be header_ptr plus header_size
    Return strong_ptr
End Process

Process called "weak_destroy" takes weak_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tears down a weak pointer to a shared/ARC object. The weak pointer holds
    a back-reference to the shared header (48 bytes). When the last weak
    reference goes away AND the strong refcount has already hit zero, the
    header itself is reclaimed; otherwise the header stays alive so other
    weak pointers can still observe the strong_count=0 state and report
    invalidation. The shared header layout is allocation_id at 0,
    generation at 8, strong_refcount at 16, weak_refcount at 24, data_size
    at 32, allocation_type at 40 - this routine must read those offsets
    exactly, since misreading either field corrupts the final munmap call.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NULL guard.
    2. Load the shared header pointer cached at weak_ptr+0.
    3. Atomically decrement weak_refcount at header+24.
    4. If weak_refcount has reached 0, load strong_refcount from header+16
       (NOT from header+0 which is the allocation_id) to decide whether
       the header is finally reclaimable.
    5. If both counts are zero, read alloc_type at header+40 and data_size
       at header+32 (these are positionally swapped relative to the
       owned-heap header; the shared header reverses them). Today shared
       objects always come from mmap, so only the ALLOC_METHOD_MMAP arm
       fires in practice, but all four arms are kept structurally to allow
       future shared-from-arena / shared-from-brk extensions to slot in
       without revisiting this finalizer.
    6. munmap (header_ptr, 48 + data_size).
    7. Free the weak-pointer structure itself.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path (only fires when both strong and weak counts hit zero in
    succession). The atomic_decrement on weak_refcount is the only fast
    operation; the conditional munmap is amortized across the lifetime of
    the shared object.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same boundary as deallocate(): reading the wrong offset from the
    header would feed attacker-controllable bytes into munmap. The
    refcount/offset reads must mirror shared_create() exactly.
    @End Security_Scope

    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get shared object header
    Let header_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with weak_ptr, 0

    If header_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Note: Decrement weak refcount
        Let weak_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 24  Note: weak_refcount at offset 24
        Let new_weak_count be proc atomic_decrement from Atomic with weak_refcount_ptr

        Note: If both strong and weak counts are 0, free header
        If new_weak_count is equal to 0:
            Note:
            Read strong_refcount from its canonical offset (header+16).
            The previous implementation read header+0 here, which is the
            allocation_id field, not the refcount - so the strong-count
            test was effectively checking whether the allocation_id was
            zero, which can never happen since IDs start at 1. That
            caused this finalizer to leak the header every time the
            data-only release path in shared_release() had already
            happened.
            :End Note
            Let strong_refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16
            Let strong_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with strong_refcount_ptr

            If strong_count is equal to 0:
                Note:
                Read allocation metadata from the shared header.
                Shared header layout (48 bytes):
                  offset 0  -> allocation_id
                  offset 8  -> generation
                  offset 16 -> strong_refcount
                  offset 24 -> weak_refcount
                  offset 32 -> data_size
                  offset 40 -> allocation_type
                The previous implementation swapped the offsets for
                alloc_method and data_size, which made alloc_method
                resolve to the user-supplied data_size (almost always a
                nonzero non-method value) and skipped every branch of
                the dispatch, leaking the header.
                :End Note
                Let data_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 32
                Let alloc_method be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 40
                Let weak_alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 0
                Let weak_generation be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with header_ptr, 8

                Note: Verify canaries before the final munmap (DEBUG=1
                Note: only). The post-canary survived shared_release's
                Note: data-zero pass because that pass intentionally
                Note: preserved it for this final check.
                If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                    Let weak_pre_canary_ptr be header_ptr plus SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
                    Let weak_pre_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with weak_pre_canary_ptr, weak_alloc_id, weak_generation
                    If weak_pre_ok is equal to 0:
                        Let weak_exp_pa be proc canary_seed_word_a with weak_alloc_id, weak_generation
                        Let weak_got_pa be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with weak_pre_canary_ptr, 0
                        Let weak_user_ptr be header_ptr plus SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
                        Set weak_user_ptr to weak_user_ptr plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
                        proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_PRE_SHARED, weak_alloc_id, weak_generation, weak_exp_pa, weak_got_pa, header_ptr, weak_user_ptr
                    End If
                    Let weak_user_ptr_for_post be header_ptr plus SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
                    Set weak_user_ptr_for_post to weak_user_ptr_for_post plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
                    Let weak_post_canary_ptr be weak_user_ptr_for_post plus data_size
                    Let weak_post_ok be proc canary_verify_redzone with weak_post_canary_ptr, weak_alloc_id, weak_generation
                    If weak_post_ok is equal to 0:
                        Let weak_exp_pb be proc canary_seed_word_a with weak_alloc_id, weak_generation
                        Let weak_got_pb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with weak_post_canary_ptr, 0
                        proc canary_fail_abort with CANARY_LOC_POST_SHARED, weak_alloc_id, weak_generation, weak_exp_pb, weak_got_pb, header_ptr, weak_user_ptr_for_post
                    End If
                End If

                Note: Free based on allocation method
                If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_MMAP:
                    If data_size is greater than 0:
                        If data_size is less than 1073741824:
                            Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
                            Let trailer_size be 0
                            If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                                Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
                                Set trailer_size to SHARED_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
                            End If
                            Let total_size be header_size plus data_size
                            Set total_size to total_size plus trailer_size
                            proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with header_ptr, total_size
                        End If
                    End If
                Otherwise If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_SHARED:
                    Note:
                    Shared header tagged with ALLOC_METHOD_SHARED (=3).
                    shared_create() writes 3 at offset 40, so the
                    common case actually falls here, not into the MMAP
                    arm. Shared objects always come from mmap (see
                    shared_create), so reclamation goes through munmap
                    on the full (header + data_size + post_canary) span.
                    :End Note
                    If data_size is greater than 0:
                        If data_size is less than 1073741824:
                            Let header_size be SHARED_HEADER_BASE_SIZE
                            Let trailer_size be 0
                            If DEBUG_ALLOCATOR_CANARIES_ENABLED is equal to 1:
                                Set header_size to header_size plus SHARED_HEADER_CANARY_SIZE
                                Set trailer_size to SHARED_HEADER_POST_CANARY_SIZE
                            End If
                            Let total_size be header_size plus data_size
                            Set total_size to total_size plus trailer_size
                            proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with header_ptr, total_size
                        End If
                    End If
                Otherwise If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_BRK:
                    Note: brk-allocated shared objects are not produced today;
                    Note: this arm exists so future brk-backed shared variants
                    Note: have a place to plug in. brk cannot free individual
                    Note: blocks, so the header would have to be parked on
                    Note: the owned-heap free list - that mechanism is
                    Note: deliberately not invoked here to avoid mixing tiers.
                Otherwise If alloc_method is equal to ALLOC_METHOD_ARENA:
                    Note: Arena-backed shared objects are not produced today;
                    Note: arena bulk-frees its entire buffer on arena_destroy,
                    Note: so per-object reclamation is intentionally a no-op.
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Free weak pointer structure itself
    proc deallocate with weak_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "weak_is_valid" takes weak_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if weak pointer still points to live object
    Note: Returns 1 if alive, 0 if deallocated or invalid

    If weak_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check cached validity flag first
    Let is_valid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Already known to be invalid
    End If

    Note: Check actual strong refcount
    Let header_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer with weak_ptr, 0
    If header_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let refcount_ptr be header_ptr plus 16  Note: strong_refcount at offset 16
    Let strong_count be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with refcount_ptr

    If strong_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Object has been deallocated - update cache
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with weak_ptr, 8, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Object is still alive
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Memory Statistics
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_page_size" returns Integer:
    Note: Standard page size on x86_64 Linux
    Return 4096
End Process

Process called "get_cache_line_size" returns Integer:
    Note: Typical L1 cache line size
    Return 64
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: C-RUNTIME COMPATIBILITY ALIASES
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The legacy v0.0.8.4.5.3.5 C runtime exported `memory_free(ptr)` as a
Note: libc free()-style wrapper. The canonical name in the Runa runtime is
Note: deallocate (defined above with full registry tracking, generation
Note: counters, and tier-aware behavior). This alias forwards so code that
Note: still spells the C name resolves at link time.

Process called "memory_free" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc deallocate with ptr
End Process
